% Title Page Information
\title{Strain-Induced Flat Bands and Lateral Heterostructures: \ Hole Localization in Rippled Monolayer TMDs}
\author{Meshal Alawein}
\degreesemester{Spring}
\degreeyear{2025}
\degree{Doctor of Philosophy}
\chair{Professor Ali Javey}
\othermembers{Professor Daryl Chrzan \\
Professor Boubacar Kant\'e}
\numberofmembers{3}
\field{Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences}
% Front Matter
\maketitle
\approvalpage
\copyrightpage
\chapter*{Abstract}
What happens when you squeeze a 2D semiconductor beyond its comfort zone? In this thesis, we demonstrate that mechanical rippling induced by controlled compression can carve out flat valence bands in 2D group-VI TMD monolayers (MoS\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}, MoSe\textsubscript{2}, and WSe\textsubscript{2}), transforming them into self-assembled lateral heterostructures with nothing more than a simple squeeze.

With first-principles calculations in hand, we follow the cascade that links mechanical rippling to electronic flat bands. Under compression, the monolayer's buckling instabilities spawn ripples that rewire the band structure, shifting $E_{\mathrm{K}}$ downward and $E_\Gamma$ upward (the latter sitting between a nearly flat segment along $\overline{\Gamma\mathrm{X}}$ and the perfectly flat line $\overline{\Gamma\mathrm{Y}}$). As the ripple amplitude grows further, a critical point is reached where $E_{\mathrm{\Gamma}}$ overtakes $E_\mathrm{K}$ and the valence‐band maximum relocates to $\Gamma$'s flat land, making the gap indirect and signaling the birth of massive holes and a new electronic identity.

This mechanical squeezing accomplishes what typically requires elaborate stacking procedures or precise twist-angle. The periodic ripples effectively carve a built-in lateral heterostructure within a single, chemically homogeneous sheet. The curvature-driven transformation creates a striking electronic asymmetry: holes become pinned in high-curvature regions with dramatically high effective mass in both directions (though much larger along $y$), while electrons remain free to roam---a quantum-mechanical sorting that emerges purely from geometry. This ripple-induced carrier segregation opens new possibilities for exciton trapping, hole-based electronics, and the study of correlated electronic phases in 2D systems.

