\chapter{Strain-Tunable 2D Systems: Fundamentals and Background}
\label{chapter:1}

\section{2D Materials: History and Promise}
\label{section:1.1}

\subsection{The Mermin--Wagner Ultimatum}
\label{subsection:1.1.1}

The story of 2D materials often starts in the same way good science usually does: with a hunch, some equations, and a whole lot of skepticism. Long before anyone actually peeled a monolayer off anything, theorists were already speculating about the exotic physics that might emerge from slicing layered crystals down to a single atomic sheet. As early as 1947, Wallace calculated the band structure of a single graphene layer and predicted its unusual semi-metallic behavior~\cite{wallace_band_1947, geim_graphene_2012}. His calculations revealed points in the Brillouin zone where the conduction and valence bands meet linearly---features we now recognize as the characteristic ``Dirac cones'' of graphene. By the 1960s, studies of graphite intercalation compounds~\cite{fischer_graphite_1978} were uncovering more hints that something interesting was happening between the layers.

But before anyone could start stacking Nobel Prizes, the growing excitement ran headlong into a theoretical wall:

\begin{theorem}[Mermin--Wagner Theorem]
For dimensions $d \leq 2$, a system with a continuous symmetry group $G$ and interactions decaying faster than $r^{-{(d+2)}}$ cannot spontaneously break $G$ at any finite temperature $T > 0$.
\end{theorem}

Translation? Atoms in a 2D sheet should jiggle themselves into oblivion at any nonzero temperature. Long-range order? Not a chance. Many physicists simply shrugged and moved on. After all, who wants to build something that's supposed to curl, ripple, or disintegrate?

Still, nature had other plans---and a quiet trick up its sleeve. It turns out that if a 2D sheet is allowed to ripple ever so slightly, it can outsmart the very theorem that tried to outlaw its existence.\footnote{Atomic-scale ripples in graphene have been experimentally confirmed~\cite{fasolino_intrinsic_2007}, and far from compromising the structure, they confer additional stability through renormalized bending rigidity.} These spontaneous undulations aren’t just aesthetic quirks---they serve a mechanical purpose.

Here’s how the loophole works. In the simplest models, out-of-plane (flexural) modes soften dangerously at long wavelengths, scaling as $\omega(\mathbf{q}) \sim |\mathbf{q}|^2$. Left unchecked, this would cause the entire lattice to wobble uncontrollably, with divergent atomic displacements. But in reality, the lattice fights back. Nature couples these flexural motions to in-plane stretching modes---an anharmonic interaction that fundamentally alters the game.

The result is a stiffening effect: the vibrational spectrum gets modified to
\begin{equation}
\omega(\mathbf{q}) = \sqrt{\frac{\kappa |\mathbf{q}|^4 + 2(\lambda + \mu)\bar{u} |\mathbf{q}|^2}{\rho}} \approx \alpha |\mathbf{q}|^2 + \beta |\mathbf{q}|^4,
\end{equation}
where $\kappa$ is the bending rigidity, $\lambda$ and $\mu$ are Lamé constants describing in-plane elasticity, and $\rho$ is the mass density~\cite{de_andres_bending_2012}. In essence, these ripples don’t weaken the sheet---they stabilize it, acting as built-in shock absorbers that tame long-wavelength instabilities.

So, in an ironic twist, the very undulations that once threatened the stability of 2D materials turn out to be their saviors. A little bending, strategically distributed, sidesteps the Mermin--Wagner constraint with surprising elegance. Still, theoretical optimism was one thing---experimental realization was another. For decades, 2D crystals remained the unicorns of solid-state physics: imagined, debated, but never observed. Until someone finally decided to try Scotch tape.


\subsection{Graphene: The First 2D Crystal}
\label{subsection:1.1.2}

In 2004~\cite{novoselov_electric_2004}, Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov---armed with nothing more than curiosity, graphite, and Scotch tape---peeled off the world's first monolayer of graphene in what they later called a ``Friday afternoon experiment'' (see Figure~\ref{fig:graphene-peel}). It was a stunt so simple it seemed absurd---yet it overturned decades of theoretical doubt and cracked open the door to a new dimension of materials science. What they uncovered wasn't just thin---it was extraordinary: a carbon sheet just one atom thick, where electrons behaved like massless particles, traveled microns without scattering, and resisted tearing with a tensile strength on par with steel. That deceptively simple Scotch-tape stunt would go on to win the 2010 Nobel Prize in Physics---and gift condensed matter physicists a new quantum playground.

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{Figures/Schematics/graphene-peel.pdf}
    \caption[Graphene exfoliation method]{\textbf{Graphene exfoliation method.} How to make history with office supplies: Mechanical exfoliation of graphene via adhesive tape. Left: Tape presses onto bulk graphite. Right: Layers peel off---sometimes down to a single sheet.}
    \label{fig:graphene-peel}
\end{figure}



\subsection{The Gapless Dilemma}
\label{subsection:1.1.3}

So why is graphene so special? The answer lies in symmetry---perfect, elegant, and profoundly powerful. Its honeycomb lattice gives each carbon atom a twin with identical surroundings, perfectly balanced in every direction. This symmetry protects the infamous Dirac cones: linear band crossings where conduction and valence bands touch but never blend. At first glance, it seemed like the dream material for electronics---fast, strong, flexible, and quantum to its core. But there was a catch: it lacks a band gap. And no band gap means no switch. For digital logic, that’s a dealbreaker.\ Without a gap, graphene can’t reliably distinguish between ``on'' and ``off'' states---its conduction is always on.\footnote{That’s like building a circuit with a light that never goes out.}  This property isn’t a flaw in the material---it’s a consequence of its perfect symmetry. This symmetry enforces the degeneracy at the Dirac points, fixing them at $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{K}'$ and preventing the opening of a band gap.\footnote{A reduction in symmetry---from C$_{6v}$ to C$_{3v}$---can lift the protection of the Dirac points and open a band gap~\cite{ponomarenko_tunable_2011}.}


So the strategies began to roll in. If nature wouldn’t give graphene a gap, perhaps we could force one into existence. One idea was to place graphene on a substrate---like SiC or hBN---in the hope that the interaction would break its symmetry just enough to open a gap~\cite{zhou_substrate-induced_2007, giovannetti_substrate-induced_2007}. Another approach involved chemical ``graffiti'': decorating the lattice with hydrogen, fluorine, or methyl groups. This created tunable gaps, but at the expense of graphene’s pristine structure~\cite{elias_control_2009, nair_fluorographene:_2010}. Researchers also tried slicing graphene into narrow nanoribbons, using lateral confinement to induce a gap---but this method proved highly sensitive to ribbon width and edge geometry~\cite{han_energy_2007, li_chemically_2008}.

A more controllable strategy emerged with bilayer stacking: stack two graphene sheets, apply a vertical electric field, and---almost magically---a tunable gap appears~\cite{zhang_direct_2009, ohta_controlling_2006}. Elegant, yes, but not without added complexity. Then came the more exotic solutions: strain engineering and moir'e superlattices, where twisting or stretching the lattice could coax the bands into opening a gap~\cite{pereira_tight-binding_2009, guinea_energy_2010}.

The trouble is, each of these methods comes at a cost---introducing defects, reducing mobility, or demanding fabrication gymnastics. Every gain feels like a trade-off. These trade-offs clarify why graphene, despite its remarkable electronic properties, remains difficult to integrate effectively into conventional semiconductor technologies.

\subsection{Beyond Graphene}
\label{subsection:1.1.4}

Graphene's gap problem may have frustrated engineers, but it ignited the imagination of physicists. Suddenly, the periodic table looked like a catalog of layered crystals---each one a potential monolayer, just waiting to be peeled and explored~\cite{ajayan_two-dimensional_2016}. What followed was an explosion of atomically thin discoveries: silicene, phosphorene, hBN, black phosphorus, and the real breakout stars---transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDs)~\cite{jariwala_emerging_2014}.

TMDs quickly became the rockstars of the post-graphene era---naturally semiconducting, mechanically flexible, and photonic to their core. The recipe is simple: take a transition metal (like Mo or W), sandwich it between two chalcogens (like S or Se), and voilà---MX$_2$, a three-atom-thick quantum sandwich~\cite{jariwala_emerging_2014, wang_electronics_2012}. Unlike graphene, these materials break inversion symmetry and exhibit strong spin--orbit coupling---offering not just charge carriers, but also spin and valley degrees of freedom to manipulate~\cite{mak_photonics_2016, xu_spin_2014}. 

Group-VI TMDs---MoS$_2$, WS$_2$, MoSe$_2$, WSe$2$---come with a remarkable feature: when thinned down to a monolayer, their indirect band gaps transform into direct ones, right in the visible range~\cite{mak_atomically_2010, kam_detailed_1982}.\footnote{For $N{\text{layers}} \ge 2$, TMDs undergo a transition from a direct to an indirect band gap due to interlayer coupling, which shifts the valence band maximum from the $\mathrm{K}$ point to $\Gamma$, and the conduction band minimum from $\mathrm{K}$ to $\mathrm{Q}$. This transition results in a significant reduction in photoluminescence intensity in multilayer samples, as shown in several studies~\cite{splendiani_emerging_2010, zhao_evolution_2013, wang_electronics_2012}.} That direct gap makes them natural-born optoelectronic materials---perfect for light emission, absorption, and everything in between~\cite{wang_electronics_2012, lopez-sanchez_ultrasensitive_2013}.

At the forefront of TMDs is MoS$_2$, celebrated for its exceptional structural and electronic versatility. In its bulk form, MoS$_2$ serves multiple roles: as a solid lubricant with a low friction coefficient ($\mu_s \sim 10^{-2}$), a photodetector material, and an efficient catalyst for hydrodesulfurization~\cite{raybaud_structural_1998, martin_superlubricity_2007}. It also features a large Seebeck coefficient~\cite{buscema_large_2013}, making it a promising candidate for thermoelectric applications.

But what makes MoS$_2$ especially compelling is how its electronic band structure evolves with thickness. In bulk, it exhibits an indirect band gap of 1.2~eV~\cite{kam_detailed_1982}, but when thinned down to a monolayer, that gap becomes direct at 1.8~eV~\cite{mak_atomically_2010}. This transition dramatically enhances photoluminescence and enables fine-tuned control over optoelectronic properties, including efficient light emission and digital on/off switching~\cite{radisavljevic_single-layer_2011, cao_valley-selective_2012, zeng_valley_2012,_

While graphene demonstrated the structural stability of two-dimensional crystals, TMDs revealed their functional potential---offering semiconducting behavior, optical activity, and electronic tunability. Their reduced dimensionality and broken symmetries give rise to quantum phenomena absent in bulk systems. Notable examples include unconventional superconductivity and superfluidity~\cite{cao_unconventional_2018, xi_ising_2016, wang_evidence_2019, lu_evidence_2015}, a variety of Hall effects~\cite{gusynin_unconventional_2005, novoselov_two-dimensional_2005, qian_quantum_2014, ma_observation_2019, kang_nonlinear_2019, deng_quantum_2020, mciver_light-induced_2020}, valley pseudospin physics~\cite{wu_electrical_2013, mak_valley_2014, cheng_valley_2014, macneill_breaking_2015, aivazian_magnetic_2015, schaibley_valleytronics_2016, singh_route_2017, zhong_van_2017, mak_lightvalley_2018, langer_lightwave_2018, xu_large_2018, zhang_abundant_2020, hu_manipulation_2020}, and nonlinear optical effects~\cite{seyler_electrical_2015, autere_nonlinear_2018, sun_giant_2019, xu_spontaneous_2020, huang_tuning_2020}.

The remarkable diversity of 2D materials beyond graphene has opened new directions in condensed matter physics and materials science, with each material family offering distinct advantages for specific applications. This landscape continues to evolve rapidly, driven by ongoing discoveries of new materials, heterostructures, and emergent phenomena~\cite{novoselov_roadmap_2012, liu_van_2016}.


