\end{table}


\subsection{Synthesis of 2D Materials}
\label{subsection:1.2.1}


If graphene opened the door, it was the flood of other 2D materials that marched through---and kept coming. Some were pursued for their exotic physics; others were recruited to fix what graphene couldn’t: a reliable, tunable band gap. This rapid expansion has been driven by a growing set of fabrication techniques, each with its own strengths and quirks. Figure~\ref{fig:synthesis} sketches the landscape---but let’s unpack it.

The first strategy is refreshingly direct. So-called \textit{top-down} methods extract layers from bulk crystals by overcoming the weak vdW forces holding them together. Mechanical exfoliation---the infamous Scotch tape method---is the pioneer here~\cite{novoselov_electric_2004}, but liquid-phase exfoliation~\cite{hernandez_high-yield_2008} has made the process more scalable, if not quite as clean.

On the flip side, \textit{bottom-up} techniques build materials atom-by-atom or molecule-by-molecule. These include chemical vapor deposition (CVD)~\cite{zhou_library_2018, tang_continuous_2017}, molecular beam epitaxy~\cite{zhuang_cooperative_2017}, and wet-chemical methods. Think of it as nanoscopic masonry: stack each atom in place, and grow your 2D crystal from scratch.

Together, these two approaches---peeling and building---have made 2D material synthesis both a science and an art. Top-down methods yield pristine flakes with minimal defects, ideal for fundamental studies. Bottom-up approaches, by contrast, promise wafer-scale coverage and industrial relevance---if one can tame their defect densities and substrate dependencies.

But what makes these materials truly exciting is their thinness. At just a few atoms thick, they offer near-ideal electrostatic control, with minimal gate leakage and strong resistance to short-channel effects---key features for next-generation transistors~\cite{geim_van_2013, ajayan_two-dimensional_2016}.

Even more powerful is their flexibility. These synthesis methods enable stacking, straining, twisting, and patterning---paving the way for engineered vdW heterostructures with emergent properties. These aren’t just materials---they’re building blocks for quantum Lego.

\begin{table}[h!]
\centering
\caption[Comparison of 2D Synthesis Methods]{\textbf{Comparison of 2D Synthesis Methods.} Advantages and limitations of top-down and bottom-up approaches for 2D material growth. Each route offers trade-offs between quality and scalability~\cite{novoselov_electric_2004, liu_exfoliation_2019, hu_two-dimensional_2018, zhou_library_2018}.}
\label{tab:synthesis_comparison}
\begin{tabular}{>{\centering\arraybackslash}m{0.23\textwidth} >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}m{0.37\textwidth} >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}m{0.37\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Approach} & \textbf{Advantages} & \textbf{Limitations} \\
\midrule
\textbf{Top-down} & Simple tools; excellent crystal quality; low defect density; retains intrinsic properties~\cite{novoselov_electric_2004} & Low yield; limited flake size; variable thickness; poor scalability~\cite{liu_exfoliation_2019} \\
\rowcolor[gray]{0.95}
\textbf{Bottom-up} & Wafer-scale growth; layer control; substrate integration; scalable fabrication~\cite{zhou_library_2018} & Higher defect density; sensitive to conditions; quality depends on substrate~\cite{hu_two-dimensional_2018} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{Figures/Schematics/synthesis.pdf}
    \caption[Top-down and Bottom-up Synthesis of 2D Materials]{\textbf{Top-down and Bottom-up Synthesis of 2D Materials.} \textbf{Left:} Exfoliation techniques (mechanical or chemical) lift monolayers from bulk. \textbf{Right:} Bottom-up growth (e.g., CVD, MBE) assembles 2D crystals atom-by-atom. Together, these methods underpin modern 2D material fabrication.}
    \label{fig:synthesis}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Strain Engineering in TMDs}
\label{subsection:1.2.2}

What makes 2D materials truly captivating isn’t just their quantum weirdness or visual elegance---it’s their flexibility. Literally. Monolayer TMDs can withstand strains exceeding 10\% without tearing~\cite{bertolazzi_stretching_2011, castellanosgomez_elastic_2012, cooper_nonlinear_2013}. This extraordinary mechanical resilience unlocks a playground for \emph{strain engineering}---the art of tuning electronic properties through carefully applied tension or compression~\cite{dai_strain_2019, qi_recent_2023}. 

This has inspired a range of experimental strategies to impose strain with varying control over magnitude, uniformity, and localization---summarized in Table~\ref{tab:strain_techniques} and illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:strain_methods}. These approaches reveal a unique advantage of 2D materials: they can maintain uniform, coherent strain across large areas---unlike their bulk counterparts, which tend to crack, shear, or form dislocations. Their atomic thinness and strong in-plane bonds mean they deform as one continuous canvas. And it’s not just about mechanics: strain profoundly alters the electronic landscape. In MoS\textsubscript{2}, for instance, strain can shift the bandgap by about 100 {meV} per 1\% strain~\cite{trainer_effects_2019}. Stretching, compressing, or wrinkling isn’t just physical---it’s a tool for electronic sculpting. That’s the promise of strain engineering: bending matter to bend bands.

\begin{table}[h!]
\centering
\caption[Strain Techniques in TMDs]{\textbf{Strain Techniques in TMDs.} Summary of methods used to apply controlled strain in monolayer TMDs, each with distinct mechanisms and outcomes.}
\label{tab:strain_techniques}
\begin{tabular}{>{\centering\arraybackslash}m{0.25\textwidth} >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}m{0.65\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Technique} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
\textbf{Substrate bending} & Curving a flexible substrate transmits strain to the overlying monolayer~\cite{conley_bandgap_2013}. \\
\rowcolor[gray]{0.95}
\textbf{Heterostructure lattice mismatch} & Stacking dissimilar 2D crystals induces strain due to lattice constant mismatches~\cite{li_molecular_2019}. \\
\textbf{AFM-tip indentation} & A nanoscale tip deforms the monolayer locally, introducing strong but localized strain~\cite{trainer_effects_2019}. \\
\rowcolor[gray]{0.95}
\textbf{Thermal mismatch} & Unequal thermal expansion between film and substrate induces strain during annealing~\cite{li_buckling_2021, han_buckling_2021}. \\
\textbf{Prestretched substrates} & Films deposited on prestretched elastomers ripple upon relaxation, inducing periodic strain~\cite{castellanosgomez_elastic_2012, vella_macroscopic_2009}. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/Schematics/TMD-strain.pdf}
  \caption[Strain-Engineering Methods in TMD Monolayers]{\textbf{Strain-Engineering Methods in TMD Monolayers.} \textbf{Top row:} (1) Substrate bending generates compressive/tensile zones, (2) lattice mismatch in heterostructures induces local strain, (3) localized strain via AFM indentation. \textbf{Bottom row:} (4) Thermal expansion mismatch, (5) prestretched substrate relaxation, (6) wrinkling on soft substrates, (7) global buckling from stiff substrate compression. Our focus lies on methods (4)-(6), where we end up with uniform periodic ripples.}
  \label{fig:strain_methods}
\end{figure}
\newpage 
\subsubsection{Controlled vs. Spontaneous Deformations}
\label{subsection:1.2.2.1}

Not all ripples are created equal. Some appear as artifacts---accidental wrinkles formed when a film is transferred onto a new substrate. Others are engineered with surgical precision. Understanding the difference is key to transforming what used to be noise into a tunable feature.

During fabrication, spontaneous ripples often arise from trapped solvents, thermal gradients, or imperfect adhesion~\cite{kim_wettingassisted_2016, liu_modified_2020, shen_rational_2021, hwang_facile_2022}. These uncontrolled features can degrade device performance by scattering carriers and introducing disorder~\cite{lee_mobility_2011, liang_toward_2011, zhu_structure_2012, wang_surface_2013}.

But with proper design, the same physical instabilities can be harnessed. Instead of fighting ripples, we can choreograph them. Controlled wrinkling lets us inscribe patterns of strain into the crystal lattice itself, reshaping how electrons move without adding a single atom.\footnote{This small act of deformation will take on a larger role later---complete with a name and its own chapter.}


\subsubsection{Mechanical Engineering of Electronic Properties}
\label{subsection:1.2.2.2}

When a TMD buckles, it doesn’t just change shape—it transforms its electronic character. Flexural deformation modifies local curvature, inducing piezoelectric and flexoelectric responses~\cite{shi_flexoelectricity_2018}, shifting band edges~\cite{qi_bandgap_2013}, and even facilitating dark exciton formation~\cite{lee_strain-induced_2023}. Mechanical shape becomes quantum function.

This idea has surprisingly deep roots. In 1909, Stoney showed that stressed films could bend a substrate~\cite{noauthor_tension_1909}—a concept later exploited to enhance transistor mobility in strained silicon~\cite{ghani_90nm_2003, mistry_delaying_2004, thompson_logic_2004}. More recently, researchers discovered that depositing 2D films onto pre-stretched elastomers leads to ripple formation upon release~\cite{castellanos-gomez_local_2013, vella_macroscopic_2009}. What began as an unwanted side effect became a design opportunity.

This evolving strain--structure--function relationship is inseparable from synthesis. High-quality monolayers are a prerequisite for generating uniform, well-controlled ripples. But the paradigm has shifted: strain is no longer a nuisance to suppress—it’s a design variable. A tunable parameter. A new axis in the phase space of quantum materials.


\section{Flat Bands: When Electrons Forget How to Move}
\label{section:1.3}

In most crystals, electrons behave like waves—free to roam, spread, and interfere as they travel through the periodic lattice. But under the right conditions, something unexpected happens: the band structure flattens. The electron’s group velocity drops to nearly zero, and its wavefunction stops spreading. The result? A flat band—where electrons all but forget how to move.

That might sound like a bad thing. Isn’t mobility what makes electronics work? But here’s the twist: when motion stops, interactions step in. With kinetic energy out of the way, even faint repulsions or attractions between electrons can reshape the ground state. Correlation becomes king.

Superconductivity, magnetism, and other collective phases don’t emerge despite the flatness—they emerge because of it. It’s precisely when electrons stop flying past each other that they start to notice each other—and act together.

This idea is no longer just theoretical. In twisted bilayer graphene (TBG) near the so-called ``magic angle,'' flat bands have driven a surge of discoveries—unconventional superconductivity, Mott-like insulating behavior, and a zoo of correlated phenomena~\cite{bistritzer_moire_2011,po_origin_2018,cao_unconventional_2018,isobe_unconventional_2018,wu_theory_2018}. What began as a moiré curiosity has quickly become a cornerstone of modern condensed matter physics~\cite{lian_twisted_2019,chou_superconductor_2019}, with experimental confirmation rolling in across multiple platforms~\cite{codecido_correlated_2019,yankowitz_tuning_2019,saito_independent_2020,shavit_theory_2021,oh_evidence_2021}.

And the physics doesn’t stop at superconductivity. Flat bands have also been linked to emergent magnetism~\cite{gonzalez-arraga_electrically_2017,sboychakov_externally_2018,sharpe_emergent_2019,wolf_electrically_2019,li_experimental_2020,pons_flat-band_2020,klebl_importance_2021,vahedi_magnetism_2021}, strange transport regimes~\cite{polshyn_large_2019,wu_phonon-induced_2019,cao_strange_2020}, and even quantum anomalous Hall effects~\cite{serlin_intrinsic_2020,bultinck_mechanism_2020,liu_theories_2021}. Entire phase diagrams have been redrawn to accommodate correlated insulators~\cite{cao_correlated_2018,yuan_erratum:_2018,padhi_doped_2018,ochi_possible_2018,zhang_correlated_2020,nuckolls_strongly_2020,da_liao_correlation-induced_2021,liu_tuning_2021,pierce_unconventional_2021}, with new tools emerging to visualize and manipulate these phases~\cite{utama_visualization_2021,ciarrocchi_excitonic_2022}.

\subsection{Twistronics: Quantum Origami}
\label{section:1.3.1}

It all started with a simple idea: take two sheets of graphene and twist one slightly on top of the other. That small rotation creates a large-scale interference pattern—a moiré superlattice—that acts like a scaffold, reshaping how electrons move through the material~\cite{bistritzer_moire_2011}. This approach came to be known as ``twistronics.''

At the so-called ``magic angle'' (around $1.1^\circ$), the bands flatten dramatically. Electron velocities drop to nearly zero across patches of momentum space, leading to a huge spike in the density of states. With kinetic energy suppressed, interactions take over—giving rise to superconductivity~\cite{cao_unconventional_2018}, correlated insulating states~\cite{cao_correlated_2018}, and rich spin and valley textures~\cite{sharpe_emergent_2019}.

As elegant as the idea is, its execution is anything but simple. Achieving the magic angle requires extreme precision—within about $\pm 0.1^\circ$—and even slight inhomogeneities across the sample can wash out the flat bands entirely. It’s like tuning a piano with a micrometer: possible, but hard to scale.

Twistronics showed what’s possible when band structure is tuned with atomic precision. But it also revealed the limits of this approach: extreme sensitivity to twist angle, narrow fabrication windows, and challenges in scalability. The physics is extraordinary—but the method remains delicate.

\section{Our Approach: Squeezing into Flatness}
\label{section:1.4}

When we first started thinking about ripples in 2D materials, we were struck by a simple observation: everyone treats them as problems to solve. The standard protocol in any fabrication lab is to minimize these corrugations, iron them out, make everything as flat as possible. But staring at AFM images of wrinkled monolayers late one evening, we couldn't help wondering---what if these ripples weren't defects at all?

This wasn't just idle speculation. We knew from prior work that TMDs are exquisitely sensitive to strain. Even tiny deformations shift their band structure. So if random wrinkles could perturb electronic properties, what might controlled, periodic ripples accomplish? The idea took hold: instead of fighting geometry, we could harness it.

We focused on the group-VI TMDs---MoS\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}, MoSe\textsubscript{2}, and WSe\textsubscript{2}---precisely because they combine mechanical flexibility with this strain sensitivity. Our approach was straightforward in concept: apply controlled uniaxial compression to a suspended monolayer and let it buckle. Not random buckling, but ordered rippling---a periodic modulation that would create alternating regions of tensile and compressive strain.

The physics we envisioned was compelling. Each ripple would act like a tiny strain field, pulling the lattice apart at peaks and squeezing it together in valleys. String enough of these together, and you'd create a one-dimensional superlattice---not by stacking different materials, but by folding a single sheet into a corrugated landscape. The electrons would see this landscape as a periodic potential, potentially strong enough to reshape their wavefunctions and confine their motion.

Our central hypothesis emerged from this thinking: systematic compression along one crystallographic direction would induce periodic rippling that breaks the material's natural symmetry. This symmetry breaking, combined with the strain-induced potential modulation, could generate fundamentally new electronic behavior---directional transport, quasi-one-dimensional confinement, perhaps even topological edge states. We were proposing to write heterostructures not with atoms, but with geometry itself. Figure~\ref{fig:ripple_sequence} illustrates the progression we anticipated: from initial compression through the buckling transition to ripple formation, ultimately leading to dramatic electronic reconstruction.

What we discovered exceeded our initial expectations. Under compression, these atomically thin sheets transformed from uniform blankets into richly textured quantum landscapes. The periodic ripples carved pathways for electrons, creating preferential directions for transport and confining carriers to quasi-one-dimensional channels. The material's electronic structure reorganized itself according to the dictates of curvature---no external gates required, no complex fabrication steps, just the pure geometric modulation doing the work.

We've come to call this approach \emph{rippletronics}: the deliberate engineering of electronic properties through controlled periodic deformation. Unlike traditional strain engineering, which typically relies on static, uniform stress fields, rippletronics exploits the dynamic interplay between curvature and electronic structure. It's a strategy where mechanical deformation becomes a design tool, where the shape of space at the nanoscale directly sculpts the quantum mechanical landscape that electrons inhabit.

In short: while our colleagues in twistronics have perfected the art of quantum origami, we propose \emph{rippletronics} as an alternative design paradigm—one where simply giving a monolayer a gentle squeeze can be just as transformative.\footnote{We will see that, sometimes, a good squeeze beats a good twist.} 


\begin{figure}[ht]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
node distance=1.3cm and 1.2cm,
every node/.style={
draw,
rectangle,
rounded corners,
minimum height=1.1cm,
minimum width=2.9cm,
align=center,
font=\small,
text=black
},
shorten >=3pt, shorten <=3pt
]
\node[fill=orange!10!white] (comp) {Compression};
\node[fill=orange!20!white, right=of comp] (buck) {Buckling\\(Transition)};
\node[fill=orange!30!white, right=of buck] (ripple) {Ripple\\Formation\\(Curvature)};
