\foreach \i/\j in {comp/buck, buck/ripple, ripple/flat}
\draw[->, thick] (\i) -- (\j);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Progression from mechanical deformation to electronic reconstruction in monolayer TMDs. The sequence shows how uniaxial compression initiates a buckling transition, leading to periodic ripple formation with inherent curvature, ultimately resulting in band flattening and hole localization. The color gradient represents the increasing degree of structural and electronic modification.}
\label{fig:ripple_sequence}
\end{figure}


\section{How This Unfolds: Structure and Organization}
\label{section:1.5}

The rest of this thesis follows the natural arc of our investigation—from atoms to ripples, from ripples to bands, and from bands to broader implications.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Chapter 2} lays the computational and physical groundwork. We define the material systems, compression protocols, and band structure signatures relevant to our study. We also describe our simulation workflow and validation procedures—laying out, step by step, how we go from geometry to quantum predictions.

    \item \textbf{Chapter 3} delves into rippletronics in action. We visualize the ripple morphology under compression, analyze how curvature reshapes the band structure, and trace the emergence of flat bands and hole localization across four TMD compositions. We also explore how ripple geometry influences confinement strength and band flattening trends.

    \item \textbf{Chapter 4} broadens the lens. We reflect on the key findings, assess rippletronics alongside twistronics, and outline the prospects for experimental realization and device design. The final sections gesture toward future directions—more ripples, more control, and perhaps more surprises.

    \item \textbf{The Appendices} contain supporting material, including full band structures and LDOS plots for each TMD, convergence studies, and technical benchmarks.
\end{itemize}


\chapter{Our Computational Framework: From Atoms to Bands}
\label{chapter:2}


\section{Compression-Induced Quantum Engineering in Monolayer TMDs}
\label{section:2.1}

2D materials provide an exceptionally tunable platform for quantum engineering. Freed from the constraints of three-dimensional crystallinity, monolayer TMD can stretch, bend, and buckle in ways that dramatically reshape their electronic behavior. When compressed uniaxially, these atomically thin sheets don't simply contract—they can wrinkle, dimple, delaminate, or buckle out-of-plane. Among these deformation modes, {periodic wrinkling} is especially compelling, as it reshapes not just the crystal lattice but the underlying quantum landscape: the electronic band structure itself.

This chapter introduces our computational framework for exploring how geometry and quantum mechanics become entangled in such systems. Our central hypothesis is simple but powerful: {by applying controlled mechanical strain, we can sculpt the electronic structure of 2D materials}. When a flat monolayer is gently squeezed, it develops a ripple pattern—creating a spatially varying potential landscape. These ripples act like nanoscale quantum wells and barriers, confining carriers, flattening bands, and enhancing interactions. The result? A strain-tunable quantum playground where geometry becomes a design knob for electronic function.

To investigate this idea, we employ a multi-scale modeling strategy that couples classical elasticity, \textit{ab initio} structural relaxation, and quantum-mechanical band structure analysis. But before we dive into the simulation machinery, let's pause to ask: \textit{why choose MoS\textsubscript{2} as our prototype?}

\vspace{1em}
\noindent
MoS\textsubscript{2} offers an ideal testbed for this study, bringing together the structural simplicity, orbital richness, and mechanical responsiveness required for meaningful strain-induced effects.

\subsection*{Atomic and Electronic Structure}

Monolayer MoS\textsubscript{2} consists of a single layer of molybdenum (Mo, $Z = 42$) atoms sandwiched between two layers of sulfur (S, $Z = 16$), forming a three-atom-thick hexagonal sheet. Mo atoms occupy trigonal prismatic coordination sites defined by the surrounding S atoms, creating strong in-plane covalent bonds and weak out-of-plane van der Waals interactions. The result is a material that is both mechanically robust and remarkably flexible—ideal for deformation-driven studies.

On the electronic side, the band structure of MoS\textsubscript{2} emerges from hybridization between Mo 4d and S 3p orbitals. Near the band edges, these interactions shape the conduction and valence bands in ways highly sensitive to strain. Figure~\ref{fig:lattice} illustrates the real-space lattice and its corresponding Brillouin zones, including both the primitive and rectangular unit cells used in our simulations.

\subsection*{Band Gap, Orbital Texture, and Valley Physics}

In its monolayer form, 1H-MoS\textsubscript{2} features a direct band gap of approximately 1.8\,eV located at the K point—a stark contrast to the indirect gap of its bulk counterpart. This direct transition enables efficient light absorption and emission, making the material attractive for photodetectors, LEDs, and solar cells.

The conduction band minimum (CBM) is primarily composed of Mo 4d$_{\text{z}^2}$ orbitals, while the valence band maximum (VBM) draws from a mix of 4d$_{\text{xy}}$ and 4d$_{\text{x}^2 - \text{y}^2}$ states, along with minor contributions from S 3p$_{\text{x}}$ and 3p$_{\text{y}}$. Crucially, spin--orbit coupling—amplified by the heavy Mo atoms—lifts degeneracies at the valence band edge. This results in distinct spin-split bands at the K and K$'$ valleys, enabling {valley-selective optical excitation}. In this regime, circularly polarized light can selectively address electrons in different valleys, laying the groundwork for valleytronic information encoding.

