\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


\subsection*{Mechanical Anisotropy and Ripple Formation}

MoS\textsubscript{2} also exhibits significant \textbf{mechanical anisotropy}. While its in-plane Young's modulus rivals that of graphene, its elastic response depends strongly on direction. Compression along the armchair (or $y$) direction induces out-of-plane buckling more readily than along the zigzag ($x$) direction—a consequence of how Mo--S bonds are oriented within the hexagonal lattice.

We capitalize on this directional softness in our simulations. By applying uniaxial compression along the armchair axis, we drive the system from a flat geometry into a periodically rippled configuration. These ripples are not just geometric curiosities; they serve as a {morphological scaffold for electronic reshaping}. As we will see in subsequent sections, ripple-induced strain modulates the local potential landscape, producing flat bands, localized carrier states, and enhanced effective masses. In short, the geometry becomes the band engineer.


\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.675\textwidth]{Figures/lattice.pdf}
  \caption[Direct- and reciprocal-space lattices of 1H-MoS\textsubscript{2}]{\textbf{Direct- and reciprocal-space lattices of 1H-MoS\textsubscript{2}.} Top: real-space lattice with Mo (light blue) and S (yellow) atoms. The primitive hexagonal unit cell is shown in light gray, and the rectangular supercell used for compression modeling is overlaid in dark gray. Bottom: corresponding Brillouin zones with the irreducible wedge for the $M \times N$ supercell.}
  \label{fig:lattice}
\end{figure}

\section{From Atoms to Bands: Computational Protocol for Compression}
\label{section:2.3}

To explore how uniaxial compression induces rippling in monolayer MoS\textsubscript{2}, we begin by constructing rectangular supercells of size $1 \times N$, extended along the armchair ($y$) direction. This geometry enables periodic deformation while preserving the in-plane hexagonal symmetry. Compression is applied incrementally along the $y$-axis, while allowing full relaxation of atomic positions in all degrees of freedom. This quasi-static approach captures the gradual evolution from a flat to a rippled morphology with high fidelity~\cite{li_buckling_2021, stewart_atomistic_2013}.

Compression is defined as:
\begin{equation}
C = -100\% \cdot \frac{L - L_0}{L_0},
\end{equation}
where $L_0$ is the equilibrium supercell length along $y$, and $L$ is the compressed length. We vary $C$ continuously from 0\% to 20\%, using fine strain increments to resolve the critical threshold at which buckling occurs.

Each strain level undergoes a three-step simulation protocol:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Classical force-field relaxation} using interatomic potentials to determine the relaxed atomic structure under compression;
  \item \textbf{DFT relaxation} of the resulting structure for quantum-level accuracy in atomic positions;
  \item \textbf{Band structure calculation} on the relaxed geometry to extract the electronic consequences of compression-induced rippling.
\end{enumerate}

All simulations employ periodic boundary conditions in-plane and include a large vacuum buffer out-of-plane to eliminate interactions between periodic images. This ensures that the resulting band structures reflect intrinsic behavior rather than finite-size or boundary artifacts.
\vspace{1em}

\section{Reading the Bands: Folding Effects and the Supercell Lens}
\label{section:2.4}

Before ripples are introduced, it is crucial to first understand the electronic structure of a pristine, unstrained monolayer. Figure~\ref{subfig:band_primitive} displays the canonical band structure of MoS\textsubscript{2}, computed using the primitive hexagonal unit cell along the high-symmetry path $\Gamma$--$\mathrm{M}$--$\mathrm{K}$--$\Gamma$. As expected, the system exhibits a direct band gap at the $\mathrm{K}$ point—a hallmark of monolayer TMDs. Just as striking is the ``Mexican hat'' curvature seen near the valence band maximum (VBM) between $\Gamma$ and $\mathrm{K}$. This subtle concavity signals a van Hove singularity in the density of states and sets the stage for flat-band formation under strain-induced perturbations.

Yet the primitive-cell framework, elegant as it is, proves too rigid for capturing long-wavelength deformations like ripples. These structures span tens of unit cells, breaking translational symmetry over extended length scales. To model them faithfully, we must adopt a new lattice geometry that accommodates both structural and electronic periodicity at ripple scale.

Figure~\ref{subfig:band_rectangular} presents the band structure of MoS\textsubscript{2} calculated using a rectangular unit cell aligned along the zigzag ($x$) and armchair ($y$) directions. This rectangularization reshapes the Brillouin zone and alters the high-symmetry path to $\Gamma$--$\mathrm{X}$--$\mathrm{S}$--$\mathrm{Y}$--$\Gamma$. At first glance, the spectrum appears more crowded, with folded bands and new apparent features. But crucially, the essential physics remains unchanged: the direct band gap persists, and the orbital character of the band edges is preserved. What has changed is the mathematical scaffolding—the way symmetry is expressed in reciprocal space.

To simulate ripple formation, we take this rectangular cell and replicate it $N$ times along the armchair direction, forming a $1 \times N$ supercell. This extended geometry allows us to resolve structural modulations with wavelengths on the order of nanometers—precisely the scale at which ripples form under compression. In reciprocal space, this elongation shrinks the Brillouin zone along $k_y$ by a factor of $N$, and the band structure becomes correspondingly folded. The folding interval is given by
\begin{equation}
\Delta k_y = \frac{2\pi}{N a},
\end{equation}
where $a$ is the unit cell length in the $y$-direction. Each band from the primitive Brillouin zone is now reproduced $N$ times, leading to a proliferation of apparent crossings, hybridizations, and mini-gaps.

This supercell approach brings distinct advantages. First, it enables the inclusion of long-wavelength strain patterns such as periodic buckling. Second, it allows for a realistic treatment of non-uniform potentials and strain gradients. Third, it reveals fine-scale electronic changes—such as effective mass renormalization or local band flattening—that are invisible in smaller cells. In effect, the supercell acts as a microscope, revealing how slowly varying geometry imprints itself on the quantum wavefunctions.

However, this power comes with a caveat. Not all features in the folded band structure correspond to physically distinct states. Many are simply mathematical echoes—artifacts of zone folding rather than genuine responses to strain. These phantom bands can obscure interpretation, especially near the band edges where subtle changes matter most. A central task in our analysis, then, is to distinguish these symmetry-induced replicas from true indicators of strain-driven physics.

To clarify the distinctions between the primitive and rectangular frameworks, we provide a detailed comparison in Table~\ref{tab:cell_comparison}. This side-by-side summary highlights the differences in real-space lattice vectors, Brillouin zone dimensions, reciprocal vectors, and use cases. Together, it forms the conceptual foundation for the ripple-induced band structure calculations presented in the chapters ahead.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[Comparison of Primitive and Rectangular Supercells]{\textbf{Comparison of Primitive and Rectangular Supercells.} Key physical and reciprocal space characteristics of the primitive hexagonal cell and the rectangular $1 \times N$ armchair supercell used in MoS\textsubscript{2} simulations.}
\label{tab:cell_comparison}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.4}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{>{\bfseries}m{4.2cm} | m{5.2cm} | m{5.2cm}}
\toprule
\textbf{Feature} & \textbf{Primitive Cell (Hexagonal)} & \textbf{Rectangular Supercell ($1 \times N$)} \\
\midrule
\textbf{Real-Space Lattice Vectors} 
& $\boldsymbol{a}_1 = a(1, 0)$ \newline $\boldsymbol{a}_2 = a(-\tfrac{1}{2}, \tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$ 
& $\boldsymbol{a}_1 = a(1, 0)$ \newline $\boldsymbol{a}_2 = Na(0, \sqrt{3})$ \\
\textbf{Physical Area} 
& $A = \tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}a^2$ 
& $A = N \sqrt{3} a^2$ \\
\textbf{Reciprocal Vectors} 
& $\boldsymbol{b}_1 = \dfrac{2\pi}{a}\left(1, \tfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)$ \newline $\boldsymbol{b}_2 = \dfrac{2\pi}{a}\left(0, \tfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\right)$ 
& $\boldsymbol{b}_1 = \dfrac{2\pi}{a}(1, 0)$ \newline $\boldsymbol{b}_2 = \dfrac{2\pi}{a}\left(0, \tfrac{1}{N\sqrt{3}}\right)$ \\
\textbf{Brillouin Zone Area} 
& $A_k = \dfrac{8\pi^2}{\sqrt{3}a^2}$ 
& $A_k = \dfrac{1}{N} \cdot \dfrac{4\pi^2}{\sqrt{3}a^2}$ \\
\textbf{IBZ Path} 
& $\Gamma$--$\mathrm{M}$--$\mathrm{K}$--$\Gamma$ 
& $\Gamma$--$\mathrm{X}$--$\mathrm{S}$--$\mathrm{Y}$--$\Gamma$ \\
\textbf{Folding Factor} 
& --- 
& $N$-fold folding along $k_y$ \\
\textbf{Example Use} 
& Pristine monolayer 
& Rippled systems \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


