\subsection*{Classical Relaxation with LAMMPS: The Sketching Phase}
\label{section:2.4.1}

Every detailed portrait begins with a sketch. In our simulations, that initial sketch is drawn using LAMMPS—the Large-scale Atomic/Molecular Massively Parallel Simulator~\cite{thompson2022lammps}. While our final goal is quantum-level accuracy, we first rely on classical mechanics to efficiently predict the large-scale structural response of MoS\textsubscript{2} monolayers under uniaxial compression. LAMMPS provides the scalability to relax large supercells—often containing thousands of atoms—allowing us to capture the emergence of long-wavelength ripple modes at low computational cost.

At the core of this approach lies Newton's second law:
\begin{equation}
m_i \ddot{\boldsymbol{r}}_i = \boldsymbol{F}_i = -\nabla_i U(\{\boldsymbol{r}_j\}),
\end{equation}
where $m_i$ and $\boldsymbol{r}_i$ are the mass and position of atom $i$, respectively, and $U$ is the total interatomic potential energy defined over the full atomic configuration $\{\boldsymbol{r}_j\}$.

\vspace{0.5em}

To model the interactions in MoS\textsubscript{2}, we employ a reactive empirical bond-order (REBO) potential~\cite{brenner_empirical_1990, liang_parametrization_2009}. This potential captures both bond formation and angular dependencies—essential ingredients for describing curvature and out-of-plane deformation. Its general form is:
\begin{equation}
U_{\mathrm{REBO}} = \sum_{i}\sum_{j>i} \left[ V^R_{ij}(r_{ij}) - \bar{b}_{ij} V^A_{ij}(r_{ij}) \right],
\end{equation}
where $V^R_{ij}$ and $V^A_{ij}$ are pairwise repulsive and attractive interactions, and $\bar{b}_{ij}$ is a bond-order term that encodes local coordination and angular geometry.

\paragraph{Minimization over Dynamics}

Although LAMMPS is designed for molecular dynamics (MD), we use it here as a static energy minimizer. Instead of integrating atomic trajectories over time, we optimize the atomic positions to find the mechanically stable configuration under a prescribed compression along the armchair ($y$) axis:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\{\boldsymbol{r}_i\}} U(\{\boldsymbol{r}_i\}) \quad \text{subject to } L_y < L_y^{(0)}.
\end{equation}
Here, $L_y$ is the compressed supercell length, and $L_y^{(0)}$ is the equilibrium length.

Two primary minimization algorithms are used in LAMMPS:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Conjugate Gradient (CG):} An efficient first-order method that updates positions using a gradient-based search direction conjugate to previous steps.
  \item \textbf{FIRE (Fast Inertial Relaxation Engine):} A hybrid method with velocity damping and adaptive step control, particularly effective in complex energy landscapes.
\end{itemize}

The update equation in these schemes takes the general form:
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{r}_i^{(n+1)} = \boldsymbol{r}_i^{(n)} + \alpha^{(n)} \boldsymbol{d}_i^{(n)},
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{d}_i^{(n)}$ is the search direction and $\alpha^{(n)}$ is an adaptive step size.

\vspace{0.5em}

\paragraph{Simulation Parameters and Setup}

The parameters used for ripple relaxation are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:lammps_params}. We adopt periodic boundary conditions in-plane and allow full atomic relaxation out-of-plane, enabling spontaneous buckling. To ensure convergence to a mechanically stable ripple, we minimize until all atomic forces fall below $10^{-4}$ eV/\AA.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[LAMMPS Parameters]{\textbf{LAMMPS Parameters.} Classical relaxation setup for generating rippled configurations under uniaxial compression.}
\label{tab:lammps_params}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.4\textwidth}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.45\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
Interatomic potential & REBO potential for MoS\textsubscript{2} \\
Strain direction & Armchair ($y$-axis) \\
Strain increments & 0.25--0.5\% per step \\
Relaxation algorithm & CG and FIRE \\
Force convergence threshold & $10^{-4}$ eV/\AA \\
Boundary conditions & Periodic (in-plane) \\
Temperature & 0 K (static) \\
Out-of-plane degrees of freedom & Fully relaxed \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Workflow Overview}

Figure~\ref{fig:LAMMPS} illustrates the classical workflow: starting from an undeformed configuration, we incrementally compress the system along $y$, minimize the total energy, and extract the ripple geometry from the resulting relaxed atomic structure.

\begin{figure}[htp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{Figures/Schematics/LAMMPS.pdf}
  \caption[LAMMPS Workflow]{\textbf{LAMMPS Workflow.} Schematic of the classical relaxation pipeline: initialize structure, apply uniaxial compression, minimize energy using CG/FIRE, and extract ripple amplitude and wavelength.}
  \label{fig:LAMMPS}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Advantages and Limitations}

Classical methods offer exceptional speed and scale, with computational complexity scaling roughly as $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$. This allows us to study supercells large enough to host realistic ripple wavelengths ($\lambda \sim 5$--$10$~nm), which would be prohibitively expensive in quantum simulations.

However, the trade-off is accuracy. Classical potentials lack the electronic degrees of freedom needed to capture charge redistribution, orbital hybridization, or band structure effects. Thus, the geometries generated by LAMMPS serve as structurally accurate, but electronically incomplete, inputs for quantum-level refinement. In that sense, LAMMPS provides the sketch—and as we show next, SIESTA fills in the quantum color.

\subsection*{DFT Refinement with SIESTA: Adding Quantum Color}
\label{section:2.4.2}

Once the classical sketch is complete, we shift to a higher-resolution tool—SIESTA (Spanish Initiative for Electronic Simulations with Thousands of Atoms)~\cite{soler_siesta_2002}—to paint the quantum mechanical details. SIESTA is a density functional theory (DFT) code that enables large-scale simulations using a linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO) basis. Its efficiency and scalability make it ideal for treating rippled monolayers where both real-space resolution and band structure fidelity are crucial.

At the heart of SIESTA's formalism lies the Kohn--Sham equation:
\begin{equation}
\left[-\frac{\hbar^2}{2m} \nabla^2 + V_{\mathrm{ext}}(\boldsymbol{r}) + V_H[\rho](\boldsymbol{r}) + V_{\mathrm{XC}}[\rho](\boldsymbol{r}) \right] \psi_i(\boldsymbol{r}) = \varepsilon_i \psi_i(\boldsymbol{r}),
\end{equation}
where $V_{\mathrm{ext}}$ is the external ionic potential, $V_H[\rho]$ is the classical Hartree potential, and $V_{\mathrm{XC}}[\rho]$ is the exchange--correlation functional capturing quantum many-body effects. The electronic density is reconstructed as
\begin{equation}
\rho(\boldsymbol{r}) = \sum_i f_i |\psi_i(\boldsymbol{r})|^2,
\end{equation}
with $f_i$ the occupation factors and $\psi_i$ the Kohn--Sham orbitals.

\paragraph{Localized Basis for Efficiency}

SIESTA expands each orbital $\psi_i$ using a finite set of strictly localized atomic-like basis functions:
\begin{equation}
\psi_i(\boldsymbol{r}) = \sum_\mu c_{i\mu} \phi_\mu(\boldsymbol{r}),
\end{equation}
where $\phi_\mu$ are confined pseudo-atomic orbitals tabulated on a radial grid. This localization leads to sparse Hamiltonians and reduces computational scaling to near-linear for large systems. Unlike plane-wave codes, SIESTA avoids vacuum penalties and enables fine resolution of strain-localized states in rippled geometries.

\paragraph{Exchange--Correlation Functional Choice}

We adopt the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) in the Perdew–Burke–Ernzerhof (PBE) form~\cite{perdew_generalized_1996}:
\begin{equation}
E_{\mathrm{XC}}[\rho] = \int \varepsilon_{\mathrm{XC}}(\rho, \nabla \rho)\, \rho(\boldsymbol{r})\, d\boldsymbol{r}.
\end{equation}
PBE captures density gradients, improving structural predictions for low-dimensional and layered systems. Though band gaps are underestimated relative to experiment, PBE remains a standard choice for relaxed geometries and qualitative band trends.

Table~\ref{tab:xc_summary} compares different exchange--correlation approximations. While we focus on GGA for all reported results, this summary serves as reference for interpreting future extensions using hybrid or van der Waals (vdW) functionals.

\begin{table}[ht]
\footnotesize
\centering
\caption[Comparison of XC Functionals]{\textbf{Comparison of Exchange--Correlation Functionals.} Typical effects of LDA, GGA, and hybrid functionals on structural and electronic predictions in TMD systems.}
\label{tab:xc_summary}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{LDA} & \textbf{GGA--PBE} & \textbf{Hybrid (e.g., HSE06)} \\
\midrule
Lattice constant $a$ & Underestimated & Slightly overestimated & Accurate \\
Bulk modulus $B$ & Overestimated & Slightly underestimated & Accurate \\
Cohesive energy $E_c$ & Too high & Slightly low & Close to experiment \\
Band gap $E_{\mathrm{gap}}$ & $\sim$50\% too low & $\sim$40--50\% too low & Approaches experimental value \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Self-Consistent Cycle and Mixing}

SIESTA solves the Kohn--Sham equations self-consistently through an iterative SCF process:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Begin with an initial guess $\rho^{(0)}(\boldsymbol{r})$
  \item Construct the Kohn--Sham Hamiltonian $H_{\mathrm{KS}}[\rho^{(n)}]$
  \item Solve for orbitals $\psi_i$ and recompute $\rho^{(n+1)}$
  \item Mix $\rho^{(n+1)}$ and $\rho^{(n)}$ to obtain the next input density
\end{enumerate}
Density mixing is stabilized using Pulay's method:
\begin{equation}
\rho^{\text{mixed}} = \alpha \rho^{(n+1)} + (1 - \alpha) \rho^{(n)} + \sum_k \beta_k \Delta \rho^{(k)},
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ is a mixing coefficient (typically 0.1--0.3), and the history terms $\Delta \rho^{(k)}$ are used to accelerate convergence.

\paragraph{SIESTA Parameters and Convergence Strategy}

All quantum calculations in this work use the setup summarized in Table~\ref{tab:siesta_params}. These values were selected based on convergence tests, balancing accuracy and efficiency for large rippled supercells.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[SIESTA Parameters]{\textbf{SIESTA Parameters.} DFT setup for structural refinement and band structure analysis of rippled MoS\textsubscript{2}.}
\label{tab:siesta_params}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.4\textwidth}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.45\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
Exchange--correlation functional & GGA--PBE \\
Basis set & DZP (double-$\zeta$ polarized) \\
Mesh cutoff & 300 Ry \\
$k$-point grid & $8 \times 6 \times 1$ (Monkhorst--Pack) \\
Vacuum spacing (out-of-plane) & $>20$~\AA \\
Electronic temperature (smearing) & 300 K \\
SCF convergence (density) & $10^{-5}$ \\
SCF convergence (energy) & $10^{-4}$~eV \\
Force convergence & 0.01~eV/\AA \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Figure~\ref{fig:SIESTA} illustrates the DFT refinement process, from input geometries to relaxed structures and resulting band structures. The diagram reflects the multi-step simulation workflow that combines classical and quantum layers.

\begin{figure}[htp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{Figures/Schematics/SIESTA.pdf}
  \caption[Quantum mechanical workflow using SIESTA]{\textbf{Quantum mechanical workflow using SIESTA.} After ripple geometries are obtained from LAMMPS, SIESTA performs structural refinement, electronic relaxation, and band structure calculation.}
  \label{fig:SIESTA}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Advantages and Limitations}

SIESTA allows us to bridge from atomistic strain to quantum observables. Its ability to handle large systems—while maintaining DFT accuracy—enables full band structure mapping of rippled supercells. However, even with localized basis sets and efficient solvers, the scaling remains roughly $\mathcal{O}(N^3)$ for dense Hamiltonians. This limits practical supercell sizes to a few thousand atoms.

Moreover, standard functionals like PBE lack accurate treatment of excitonic effects, long-range dispersion, and strongly correlated phenomena. For these effects, more advanced methods (e.g., GW or hybrid functionals) may be necessary, though they are computationally more demanding.

Nonetheless, within its regime of validity, SIESTA provides a reliable quantum lens to analyze how geometric ripples reshape the electronic landscape of MoS\textsubscript{2}. In the next section, we transition from calculation to interpretation—quantifying the ripple geometry and decoding its quantum mechanical consequences.

\section{From Bits to Insights: Our Analysis Methodology}
\label{section:2.6}

With both structural and electronic data in hand, we now turn to the final stage: extracting physical insight from atoms and orbitals. Our workflow converts raw output from LAMMPS and SIESTA into quantitative metrics that describe ripple morphology, band flattening, orbital contributions, and electronic localization. These analyses form the backbone of our conclusions about curvature-induced quantum effects.

\vspace{0.5em}
\subsection*{Structural Analysis: Mapping the Nanoscale Landscape}

The first task is to characterize the geometry of each relaxed configuration as a function of applied strain. For rippled monolayers, key geometric quantities include amplitude, wavelength, curvature, and local bond strain. These are derived directly from the atomic positions:

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[Ripple Geometry Metrics]{\textbf{Ripple Geometry Metrics.} Definitions of key structural parameters extracted from LAMMPS- and SIESTA-relaxed configurations.}
\label{tab:ripple_geometry}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.28\textwidth}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.63\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Quantity} & \textbf{Definition} \\
\midrule
Amplitude $A$ & Peak-to-peak out-of-plane displacement of Mo atoms: $A = \max(z_i) - \min(z_i)$ \\
Wavelength $\lambda$ & Fitted from the sinusoidal model: $z(y) = A \sin\left(\frac{2\pi y}{\lambda} + \phi\right)$ \\
Curvature $\kappa_{\max}$ & Max curvature from fitted profile: $\kappa_{\max} = \dfrac{4\pi^2 A}{\lambda^2}$ \\
Bond-level strain & Relative changes in Mo--S bond lengths and S--Mo--S angles vs.\ pristine values \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

These geometric parameters serve as direct proxies for the local strain landscape experienced by charge carriers. In particular, curvature $\kappa(y)$ creates spatially varying potentials that drive quantum confinement and electronic band modulation.

\vspace{0.5em}

\section{Electronic Analysis: Decoding the Quantum Response}

Once ripples emerge under uniaxial compression, the resulting curvature sculpts more than just atomic positions—it reshapes the electronic landscape itself. Bands bend, orbitals mix, and charge carriers begin to congregate in curved pockets of the crystal. To systematically track these transformations, we extract a suite of electronic observables from our SIESTA-computed band structures and wavefunctions. While our primary focus lies in characterizing band flatness, charge localization, and orbital hybridization near the valence band edge, we present a broader set of metrics for completeness and future reference.

\subsection{Mathematical Definitions of Core Metrics}

We compute seven key metrics directly from our DFT band structures, focusing on the top valence band (\text{VB1}). Here are their precise mathematical forms:

\subsubsection{1. Total Bandwidth}

\begin{equation}
    W_{\text{total}} = \max_{k} E_{\text{VB1}}(k) - \min_{k} E_{\text{VB1}}(k)
\end{equation}

This measures the full energy spread of the valence band across the entire Brillouin zone.

\subsubsection{2. Directional Bandwidths}

\begin{equation}
    W_{\Gamma K} = \bigl|E_{\text{VB1}}(K) - E_{\text{VB1}}(\Gamma)\bigr|
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    W_{\Gamma X} = \bigl|E_{\text{VB1}}(X) - E_{\text{VB1}}(\Gamma)\bigr|
\end{equation}

These probe anisotropic shifts along high-symmetry directions in both hexagonal and rectangular supercell formulations.

\subsubsection{3. Flat-Region Detection}

First, we locate the valence band maximum:
\begin{equation}
    k_{\text{VBM}} = \arg\max_k E_{\text{VB1}}(k), \quad E_{\text{VBM}} = \max_k E_{\text{VB1}}(k)
\end{equation}

Next, we compute the second derivative (curvature) on a fine \( k \)-grid \( k_f \):
\begin{equation}
    \frac{d^2E}{dk^2}(k_f)
\end{equation}

The ``flat'' mask is defined by the conjunction of two conditions:
\begin{equation}
    \left|\frac{d^2E}{dk^2}(k_f)\right| < \epsilon \, \max_{k_f}\left|\frac{d^2E}{dk^2}(k_f)\right| 
    \quad \wedge \quad 
    |k_f - k_{\text{VBM}}| < k_{\text{cutoff}}
\end{equation}

This identifies contiguous \( k \)-segments \(\{[a_i,b_i]\}\) satisfying the flatness criterion.

\subsubsection{4. Flat-Region \( k \)-Length}

\begin{equation}
    \Delta k_{\text{flat}} = \max_i (b_i - a_i)
\end{equation}

This represents the largest momentum span of any identified flat segment.

\subsubsection{5. Flat-Region Bandwidth}

\begin{equation}
    W_{\text{flat}} = \max_{k\in\text{flat}}E_{\text{VB1}}(k) - \min_{k\in\text{flat}}E_{\text{VB1}}(k)
\end{equation}

The energy width within the flat region, evaluated via spline interpolation on the selected \( k \)-points.

\subsubsection{6. Flatness Ratio}

Define the total \( k \)-span:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta k_{\text{total}} = \max_k k - \min_k k
\end{equation}

Then the flatness ratio is:
\begin{equation}
    \alpha_{\text{flat}} = 100 \times \frac{\Delta k_{\text{flat}}}{\Delta k_{\text{total}}} \, \%
\end{equation}

The percentage of the Brillouin zone satisfying our flatness threshold.

\subsubsection{7. IPR Proxy}

\begin{equation}
    \text{IPR\_proxy} = \frac{1}{\Delta k_{\text{flat}} \times W_{\text{flat}}}
\end{equation}

An inverse measure of kinetic energy in the flat region, serving as a band-structure-derived estimate of real-space localization.

\subsection{Analysis Criteria}

Our analysis employs the following specific thresholds:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Flat segments defined by curvature threshold:
    \[
    \left|\frac{d^2E}{dk^2}\right| < 5\%\times \max \left|\frac{d^2E}{dk^2}\right|
    \]

    \item Momentum (\( k \))-window around VBM:
    \[
    \pm 0.20 \, \mathrm{\AA}^{-1}
    \]

    \item \( W_{\mathrm{flat}} \) is the maximum \( \Delta E \) within the identified flat segments.

    \item IPR proxy calculation:
    \[
    \mathrm{IPR\_proxy} = \frac{1}{\Delta k_{\mathrm{flat}} \cdot W_{\mathrm{flat}}}
    \]
\end{enumerate}

\begin{table*}[ht]
\small
\centering
\caption[Electronic Observables from DFT]{\textbf{Electronic Observables from DFT.} Key quantities used to characterize curvature-induced quantum effects in rippled MoS\textsubscript{2}, including band flattening, carrier localization, and orbital hybridization. While only a subset is used in our core analysis, we present the full set for reference and completeness.}
\label{tab:electronic_metrics}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.35}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{4.2cm} >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{11.8cm}}
\toprule
\textbf{Quantity} & \textbf{Definition and Physical Interpretation} \\
\midrule
\textbf{Band gap} $E_{\mathrm{gap}}$ & $E_{\mathrm{CBM}} - E_{\mathrm{VBM}}$; measures the fundamental energy gap between conduction and valence bands. A key indicator of semiconducting behavior and its modulation under strain. \\
\textbf{Effective mass tensor} ${m}^*_{ij}$ & $\left(m^{-1}\right)_{ij} = \frac{1}{\hbar^2} \left. \frac{\partial^2 E}{\partial k_i \partial k_j} \right|_{\vb{k}_0}$; reflects the local curvature of a band near extrema and determines carrier mobility and anisotropic confinement. \\
\textbf{Total bandwidth} $W_{\mathrm{total}}$ & $E_{\mathrm{max}} - E_{\mathrm{min}}$; total energy spread of a given band across the Brillouin zone. Smaller values correspond to flatter bands and suppressed kinetic energy. \\
\textbf{Flat bandwidth} $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$ & Energy width of the nearly dispersionless segment of the valence band. Quantifies the degree of flattening induced by curvature. \\
\textbf{Directional bandwidth} $W_{\Gamma\mathrm{K}}$ & $|E(\Gamma) - E(\mathrm{K})|$ in the hexagonal Brillouin zone; captures anisotropic shifts in the valence band under strain. \\
\textbf{Directional bandwidth} $W_{\Gamma\mathrm{X}}$ & $|E(\Gamma) - E(\mathrm{X})|$ in rectangular supercells; equivalent directional bandwidth in the folded zone formalism. \\
\textbf{Flatness ratio} $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ & $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}} = \dfrac{k_{\mathrm{flat}}}{k_{\mathrm{total}}}$, where $k_{\mathrm{flat}}$ is the cumulative $k$-length over which $\left|\frac{d^2E}{dk^2}\right|$ falls below 5\% of its maximum value. Reflects how broadly the flat region extends in momentum space. \\
\textbf{IPR proxy} (flatness-based) & $\text{IPR}_\text{proxy} \sim 1 / (W_{\mathrm{flat}} \cdot \alpha_{\mathrm{flat}})$; a band-structure-derived estimate of real-space localization. Useful when wavefunction data is unavailable. \\
\textbf{Inverse Participation Ratio (IPR)} & $\text{IPR} = \dfrac{\int |\psi(\vb{r})|^4 d\vb{r}}{\left( \int |\psi(\vb{r})|^2 d\vb{r} \right)^2}$; measures the degree of real-space localization. High values indicate confinement to narrow ripple troughs. \\
\textbf{Total density of states (DOS)} $D(E)$ & $D(E) = \sum_n \delta(E - \varepsilon_n)$; counts the number of available electronic states per energy. Computed with Gaussian broadening; peaks correspond to van Hove singularities. \\
\textbf{Projected DOS (PDOS)} $D_\mu(E)$ & $D_\mu(E) = \sum_n |\braket{\phi_\mu | \psi_n}|^2 \delta(E - \varepsilon_n)$; decomposes the DOS by atomic orbital or atom type. Used to trace how curvature modifies orbital hybridization. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table*}

\paragraph{When Is a Band Truly Flat?}\mbox{}\\[1ex]

To avoid mistaking shallow curvature for genuine flatness, we establish thresholds for classifying flat bands based on the joint behavior of bandwidth, extent, and localization:
\begin{itemize}
  \item A band is \textbf{nearly flat} if $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$ falls in the range of 100--200~meV with moderate curvature.
  \item A band is \textbf{fully flat} if:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item $W_{\mathrm{flat}} < 50$~meV (i.e., less than twice $k_B T$ at room temperature),
      \item $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}} > 0.1$ (at least 10\% of the BZ is flat),
      \item $\text{IPR} > 0.1$ (the wavefunction is appreciably localized).
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

This classification distinguishes physical confinement from visual illusions. In fact, some bands near the $\Gamma$ point appear flat but exhibit increasing $W_{\Gamma\mathrm{K}}$ under compression---a phenomenon we term the ``bandwidth paradox.'' It arises from orbital-selective responses to strain: out-of-plane Mo $d_{z^2}$ states at $\Gamma$ shift differently than in-plane $d_{xy}$ or $d_{x^2 - y^2}$ states at $\mathrm{K}$, leading to deceptive flattening in energy plots without genuine localization.

\paragraph{Mathematical Relationship Between IPR and Band Flatness}

The inverse participation ratio (IPR) is a foundational metric for quantifying electronic localization in real space. For a wavefunction $\psi(\boldsymbol{r})$, the IPR is defined as
\begin{equation}
\text{IPR} = \frac{\int |\psi(\boldsymbol{r})|^4 \, d\boldsymbol{r}}{\left( \int |\psi(\boldsymbol{r})|^2 \, d\boldsymbol{r} \right)^2},
\end{equation}
which measures the extent to which the wavefunction is concentrated spatially. Delocalized states yield IPR values approaching $1/L^2$, where $L$ is the system size, while perfectly localized states approach IPR~$\approx 1$.

When real-space wavefunctions are unavailable, we approximate localization using an IPR proxy derived from band flatness metrics. Specifically, we propose the relationship
\begin{equation}
\text{IPR}_{\text{proxy}} \propto \frac{1}{W_{\mathrm{flat}} \cdot \alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}},
\end{equation}
where $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$ is the flat bandwidth and $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ is the flatness ratio. Physically, this makes sense: as $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$ decreases, band dispersion is suppressed, leading to more localized states. The role of $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ is more nuanced: while a larger $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ indicates broader flatness in $k$-space, the Fourier uncertainty principle implies that flatter and more localized regions in $k$ correspond to tighter confinement in real space. Thus, this product inversely captures confinement strength.

In twisted bilayer systems and rippled TMDs, this localization has been directly observed using scanning tunneling microscopy, especially near ``magic angles'' or strain values that induce ultra-flat bands. The IPR-flatness relationship offers a practical route for estimating localization without expensive wavefunction calculations, enabling efficient screening of 2D materials for correlated or confined electronic phases.

In the chapters that follow, we will apply a focused subset of these metrics---particularly the band gap $E_{\mathrm{gap}}$, the effective mass tensor $m_{ij}^*$, the flat bandwidth $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$, and the flatness ratio $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$---to dissect the emergence of localized hole states, curvature-induced band flattening, and ripple-driven quantum modulation in monolayer MoS\textsubscript{2}.


\subsection*{Summary: A Two-Layered View of Rippletronics}

Our methodology integrates classical mechanics and quantum electronic structure into a unified pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Classical layer (LAMMPS):} Captures ripple formation under strain and extracts geometric descriptors ($A$, $\lambda$, $\kappa$).
  \item \textbf{Quantum layer (SIESTA):} Refines the relaxed structure and computes $E_{\mathrm{gap}}$, $m^*_{ij}$,  $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$, and $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ to reveal how curvature reshapes the band structure and influences localization.
\end{enumerate}

In essence, we turn mechanical deformation into a tuning knob for quantum localization. As we will see in the next chapter, certain strains bring forth a fascinating transition: the emergence of flat bands, sharply localized holes, and a ripple-induced quantum playground.


\chapter{Rippletronics: Structural Sculpting of Electronic Bands}
\label{chapter:3}

\section{Conceptual Overview: Squeezing Bands Flat}
\label{section:3.1}

To understand how periodic ripples impact electronic properties, we begin by revisiting the central idea: applying in-plane compressive strain causes a monolayer to buckle out-of-plane, forming a spatially periodic ripple structure~\cite{fang_electronic_2018,stewart_atomistic_2013}. These geometric modulations produce alternating regions of tensile and compressive strain, effectively reshaping the local potential landscape at the atomic scale. 

What happens next is subtle but profound. The periodic strain fields induced by rippling fold the Brillouin zone, hybridize electronic states, and—most importantly—trigger the emergence of nearly flat bands near the valence band edge.

Unlike the flat bands seen in twisted bilayer graphene and other moiré systems, which arise from interlayer interference, the rippletronics route relies solely on intralayer strain modulation. That means we can flatten bands without stacking two layers or dialing in a magic twist angle. All it takes is a bit of compression—and the quantum landscape transforms.

Because the ripple pattern is defined by the monolayer’s geometry, it is continuously tunable. The more we compress, the deeper the ripples become—and the more strongly the band structure is reshaped. This mechanical route to flat-band physics is not only conceptually elegant but also experimentally scalable, offering a new degree of freedom for designing quantum materials from the ground up.

\section{Visualizing Rippled Structures}
\label{section:3.2}

We begin by visualizing how the monolayer geometry evolves under increasing uniaxial compression. As the strain rises from 0\% to 15\%, the initially flat MoS\textsubscript{2} sheet undergoes a buckling transition, forming a regular sinusoidal ripple pattern. This transition is clearly captured in both side-view heightmaps and 3D renderings of the relaxed atomic structure~\cite{li_buckling_2021,han_buckling_2021}.

