\label{fig:band_flattening_new}
\end{figure}


This flattening reduces the group velocity of charge carriers and foreshadows their localization in real space—a connection we explore soom.



\subsection{Effective Mass and Transport: When Holes Diet, They Gain Weight}
\label{subsection:3.3.3}

As the valence band flattens, its carriers grow sluggish. This behavior is captured quantitatively by the effective mass tensor \( m^*_{ij} \), which characterizes how easily electrons or holes accelerate under an applied field. In band theory, it is given by:

\begin{equation}
\left(m^{*-1}\right)_{ij} = \frac{1}{\hbar^2} \left. \frac{\partial^2 E(\mathbf{k})}{\partial k_i \, \partial k_j} \right|_{\mathbf{k}_0},
\end{equation}

where \( \mathbf{k}_0 \) is the location of the band extremum. In practice, we extract \( m^*_{ij} \) by fitting a quadratic function to the band edge within a \( \pm 0.1~\text{\AA}^{-1} \) window along each principal direction.

Physically, the curvature of the band determines how fast a particle can move: steep curvature implies a light mass and high mobility, while flat curvature leads to massive, slow carriers. The analogy is intuitive—electrons in flat bands are like hikers wading through mud.

Figure~\ref{fig:meff_MoS2} shows the evolution of the effective mass in MoS\textsubscript{2} under compression. The left panel tracks the conduction band effective mass (\( m^*_{e,xx} \), \( m^*_{e,yy} \)), which changes modestly with strain. In contrast, the right panel reveals a dramatic increase in the hole effective mass (\( m^*_{h,xx} \), \( m^*_{h,yy} \)) beyond 7–8\% compression—coinciding with the flattening of the valence band and its relocation from K to $\Gamma$.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2_effective_masses_1x10.pdf}
\caption[Effective Mass Evolution in MoS\textsubscript{2}]{\textbf{Effective Mass Evolution in MoS\textsubscript{2}.} Left: electron effective masses along \( x \) and \( y \). Right: hole effective masses. After 8\% compression, hole masses grow sharply, especially along \( y \), reflecting strong band flattening and localization.}
\label{fig:meff_MoS2}
\end{figure}

To pinpoint the transition, we isolate \( m^*_{h,yy} \) at key $k$-points: the original VBM at K, the new VBM near $\Gamma$, and the highest occupied state across the Brillouin zone (VBM). As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:mh_yy_VBM}, the mass at K remains light, but \( m^*_{h,yy}(\Gamma) \) increases steadily, eventually overtaking K around 9\% strain. After this point, the VBM lies within a flat segment near $\Gamma$, and the corresponding hole effective mass diverges—signaling the onset of heavy, localized holes.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2_1x10_mhyy_comparison.pdf}
\caption[Hole Effective Mass at Key $k$-Points]{\textbf{Hole Effective Mass at Key $k$-Points.} The \( yy \)-component of the hole effective mass is shown for the VBM (red), $\Gamma$ (orange), and K (black stars). Beyond 9\% strain, the VBM shifts to $\Gamma$, and \( m^*_{h,yy} \) increases steeply as the band flattens.}
\label{fig:mh_yy_VBM}
\end{figure}

This dramatic mass enhancement has direct consequences for carrier mobility. Within the Drude model,
\begin{equation}
\mu = \frac{e \tau}{m^*},
\end{equation}
where \( \tau \) is the scattering time. Assuming \( \tau \) remains roughly constant, a 10× increase in \( m^* \) leads to a 10× drop in mobility. Effectively, holes freeze in place as their bands flatten—a hallmark of localization.

Compression also introduces pronounced anisotropy. Since strain is applied along \( y \), the ripple curvature—and hence the band flattening—is strongest in that direction. As a result, \( m^*_{h,yy} \gg m^*_{h,xx} \) at high strain. The anisotropy ratio \( m^*_{h,yy} / m^*_{h,xx} \) exceeds 3 after 10\% compression, implying that holes can move more freely across ripples than along them. This creates a directionally selective transport channel—essentially a nanoscale one-way street engineered via geometry.

In summary, flattening of the valence band leads to:

\begin{itemize}
  \item Divergence of hole effective mass near $\Gamma$
  \item Strong suppression of hole mobility
  \item Emergent anisotropy in transport
\end{itemize}

These effects are signatures of a system entering the flat-band regime—where geometry reshapes not only the band structure, but the very inertia of electronic carriers.



\subsection{Localization in Real Space: Electron Pockets and Puddles}
\label{subsection:3.3.2}

The real-space consequence of band flattening is carrier localization---a phenomenon rooted in the Heisenberg uncertainty principle:
\begin{equation}
\Delta x \cdot \Delta p \geq \frac{\hbar}{2}.
\end{equation}
As the band flattens in momentum space, the corresponding spread in momentum $\Delta p$ narrows, forcing $\Delta x$ to grow smaller. In physical terms: a flatter band implies heavier, slower-moving carriers that become increasingly confined in space.

Figure~\ref{fig:ldos_strain_series} shows the local density of states (LDOS) for the conduction band minimum (CBM, top panels) and valence band maximum (VBM, bottom panels) in MoS\textsubscript{2}, projected onto the $yz$-plane at various compressions. At low strain (0--3\%), both CBM and VBM states remain delocalized, spanning the entire ripple. But beginning around 7--8\% compression, the VBM states begin to concentrate at the crests and troughs of the ripple geometry. These regions of maximal curvature act as quantum wells, trapping holes into sharply localized pockets.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering

\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_0.png}
\caption{$0\%$}
\end{subfigure}
\hfill
\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_3.png}
\caption{$3\%$}
\end{subfigure}

\vspace{1em}

\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_7.png}
\caption{$7\%$}
\end{subfigure}
\hfill
\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_8.png}
\caption{$8\%$}
\end{subfigure}

\vspace{1em}

\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_10.png}
\caption{$10\%$}
\end{subfigure}
\hfill
\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_15.png}
\caption{$15\%$}
\end{subfigure}

\caption[LDOS Under Increasing Strain in MoS\textsubscript{2}]{\textbf{LDOS Under Increasing Strain in MoS\textsubscript{2}.} Cross-sections of the local density of states for conduction (top) and valence (bottom) band edges, projected onto the $yz$-plane. At low strain, states are delocalized. As compression increases, hole states become trapped at ripple extrema, forming curvature-defined quantum wells.}
\label{fig:ldos_strain_series}
\end{figure}

This localization is not just geometric---it reflects a change in the orbital character of the wavefunctions. As shown in real-space wavefunction projections (Figure~\ref{fig:wavefn}), the localized VBM states derive primarily from Mo 4$d_{z^2}$ orbitals and S 3$p$ orbitals located on the tensile side of the ripple (outer bend). These orbitals form tightly bound states at high curvature regions, effectively forming a chain of laterally modulated quantum wells. In contrast, CBM states remain largely delocalized and maintain uniform spread across the ripple, even at high compression. This electron--hole asymmetry gives rise to spontaneous spatial charge separation: trapped holes at ripple extrema and mobile electrons between them.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2/1x10/LDOS/LDOS_CB_VB_1x10_15.png}
\caption[Zoomed Image of MoS$_2$ LDOS Showing Orbitals Hybridization]{\textbf{Orbital Hybdrization in MoS$_2$.} Probability densities for the CBM and VBM compression 15\%, illustrating how hole states localize at regions of maximum curvature while electron states remain extended. VBM states exhibit strong contributions from Mo $d_{z^2}$ and S $p$ orbitals on the tensile side of the ripple.}
\label{fig:wavefn}
\end{figure}

The emergence of these localized states coincides with the valence band maximum shifting from K to $\Gamma$, where the band curvature flattens dramatically. This is accompanied by a sharp rise in the hole effective mass, particularly along the compression direction ($m_{h,yy}^*$), as discussed in Section~\ref{subsection:3.3.3}. Beyond 9\% strain, the VBM resides within the flat segment near $\Gamma$, giving rise to nearly dispersionless hole states and strong real-space confinement.

In essence, the ripple turns the TMD monolayer into a natural lateral heterostructure: regions of high curvature act as quantum wells, while flatter inflection zones serve as weakly confining barriers. Without any chemical modification or interlayer stacking, geometry alone reconfigures the quantum transport landscape---modulating carrier localization and setting the stage for strongly correlated states.


\section{Comparative Analysis of Compression-Dependent Properties Across TMD Compositions}
\label{section:3.4}

So far, we've focused our attention on MoS\textsubscript{2}, but rippletronics is no one-material show. Other monolayer TMDs—particularly MoSe\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}, and WSe\textsubscript{2}—undergo analogous curvature-induced electronic transformations, albeit with unique mechanical and electronic fingerprints. Each material exhibits a characteristic compression-induced electronic evolution.

To compare their behavior systematically, we extract four key metrics across a compression range of 5\% to 20\%:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Band gap \( E_g \)
  \item Ripple amplitude $A$
  \item Ripple wavelength $\lambda$
  \item Maximum curvature \( \kappa_{\mathrm{max}} \)
\end{enumerate}

Figure~\ref{fig:tmd_summary} shows how these quantities evolve with compression. Several trends immediately stand out: band gaps follow a clear hierarchy where sulfides maintain higher values than selenides, and tungsten-containing compounds exhibit larger gaps than their molybdenum analogs, with WS\textsubscript{2} showing the highest values throughout; ripple amplitude increases steadily with compression, with selenides reaching larger values than sulfides and tungsten-containing compounds showing higher amplitudes than their molybdenum counterparts; wavelength contracts uniformly, with tungsten-containing TMDs maintaining consistently shorter wavelengths than molybdenum-containing ones and sulfides displaying larger wavelengths than selenides; and maximum curvature rises nonlinearly, with selenides achieving the highest values and tungsten-containing compounds exhibiting greater curvature than their molybdenum analogs at large compression. The net result is a tunable palette of geometric and electronic responses.\ The systematic trends across metal and chalcogen species are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:tmd_trends}.


\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Systematic trends in compression-dependent properties across TMD families}
\label{tab:tmd_trends}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{Metal Effect} & \textbf{Chalcogen Effect} & \textbf{Overall Ranking} \\
& (W vs Mo) & (S vs Se) & (Highest $\rightarrow$ Lowest) \\
\midrule
Band gap ($E_g$) & W $>$ Mo & S $>$ Se & WS\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoS\textsubscript{2} $>$ WSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoSe\textsubscript{2} \\
Amplitude ($A$) & W $>$ Mo & Se $>$ S & WSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ WS\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoS\textsubscript{2} \\
Wavelength ($\lambda$) & W $<$ Mo & S $>$ Se & MoS\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ WS\textsubscript{2} $>$ WSe\textsubscript{2} \\
Curvature ($\kappa$) & W $>$ Mo & Se $>$ S & WSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoSe\textsubscript{2} $>$ WS\textsubscript{2} $>$ MoS\textsubscript{2} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{Figures/TMDs_Properties.pdf}
\caption[Compression-Dependent Properties Across TMDs]{\textbf{Compression-Dependent Properties Across TMDs.} \textbf{Top left:} Band gap $E_g$ decreases with increasing compression. \textbf{Top right:} Ripple amplitude $A$ grows steadily with compression. \textbf{Bottom left:} Wavelength $\lambda$ contracts under compression. \textbf{Bottom right:} Curvature $\kappa$ rises nonlinearly with compression. See Table~\ref{tab:tmd_trends} for systematic trends across TMD families.}
\label{fig:tmd_summary}
\end{figure}

To model the compression-dependent evolution of these properties quantitatively, we performed systematic fits to the extracted data. Specifically, we fitted the compression dependence of $E_g$, $A$, and $\lambda$ to quadratic functions:
\begin{equation}
f(C) = a_2 C^2 + a_1 C + a_0,
\end{equation}
and modeled the curvature $\kappa(C)$ using a power-law relationship:
\begin{equation}
\kappa(C) = \mu C^\nu + \omega,
\end{equation}
where \( C \) is the applied compression percentage. The extracted fit parameters are listed in Table~\ref{tab:tmd_fits}. These analytical expressions enable prediction of material properties at arbitrary compression levels within the studied range (5-20\%), facilitating device design without exhaustive computational sampling.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[Compression-Fit Parameters for TMDs]{\textbf{Compression-Fit Parameters for TMDs.} Quadratic fits are used for $E_g$, $A$, and $\lambda$, while $\kappa(C)$ is modeled using a power law. Fit coefficients capture each material's curvature sensitivity and mechanical compliance.}
\label{tab:tmd_fits}
\begin{tabular}{llcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{MoS\textsubscript{2}} & \textbf{MoSe\textsubscript{2}} & \textbf{WS\textsubscript{2}} & \textbf{WSe\textsubscript{2}} \\
\midrule
\multirow{3}{*}{$E_g$ [eV]}
& $a_2$ & $-5.60\!\times\!10^{-4}$ & $-7.07\!\times\!10^{-4}$ & $-4.88\!\times\!10^{-4}$ & $-1.04\!\times\!10^{-3}$ \\
& $a_1$ & $-0.0132$ & $-0.0080$ & $-0.0127$ & $-0.0034$ \\
& $a_0$ & $1.838$ & $1.544$ & $1.965$ & $1.698$ \\
\midrule
\multirow{3}{*}{$A$ [\AA]}
& $a_2$ & $-0.0169$ & $-0.0131$ & $-0.0131$ & $-0.0089$ \\
& $a_1$ & $0.953$ & $0.744$ & $0.797$ & $0.643$ \\
& $a_0$ & $5.49$ & $10.17$ & $7.81$ & $11.54$ \\
\midrule
\multirow{3}{*}{$\lambda$ [\AA]}
& $a_2$ & $0$ & $4.42\!\times\!10^{-3}$ & $1.20\!\times\!10^{-3}$ & $3.94\!\times\!10^{-4}$ \\
& $a_1$ & $-0.549$ & $-0.640$ & $-0.586$ & $-0.587$ \\
& $a_0$ & $54.86$ & $55.07$ & $54.69$ & $54.36$ \\
\midrule
\multirow{3}{*}{$\kappa_{\text{max}}$ [1/\AA]}
& $\mu$   & $0.0069$ & $0.0075$ & $0.0052$ & $0.0032$ \\
& $\nu$   & $1.021$  & $0.976$  & $1.100$  & $1.257$ \\
& $\omega$ & $0.036$ & $0.063$  & $0.054$  & $0.084$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

To quantitatively characterize band flattening, we employ several complementary metrics:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Flat bandwidth} \( W_{\mathrm{flat}} \): The energy range (in meV) over which the valence band remains nearly flat, computed as:
  \begin{equation}
  W_{\mathrm{flat}} = \max_{k\in\text{flat}}E_{\text{VB1}}(k) - \min_{k\in\text{flat}}E_{\text{VB1}}(k)
  \end{equation}
  
  \item \textbf{Flatness ratio} \( \alpha_{\mathrm{flat}} \): The fraction of the Brillouin zone where band curvature is negligible:
  \begin{equation}
  \alpha_{\mathrm{flat}} = \frac{\Delta k_{\mathrm{flat}}}{\Delta k_{\mathrm{total}}} \times 100\%
  \end{equation}
  where flat regions satisfy $|d^2E/dk^2| < 0.05 \times \max|d^2E/dk^2|$.

  \item \textbf{IPR proxy}: A figure of merit (FOM) derived from band structure properties to estimate real-space localization without computing wavefunctions:
  \begin{equation}
  \text{IPR}_{\text{proxy}} = \frac{1}{\Delta k_{\mathrm{flat}} \times W_{\mathrm{flat}}}
  \end{equation}
  This quantity increases as bands become flatter (smaller $W_{\mathrm{flat}}$) and more localized in $k$-space (smaller $\Delta k_{\mathrm{flat}}$), serving as a computationally efficient proxy for the true Inverse Participation Ratio.
\end{enumerate}

The evolution of valence band structure under compression (Figure~\ref{fig:tmds_valence_bands}) reveals a fundamental distinction between sulfide and selenide TMDs. All materials exhibit complete band flattening along the transverse direction ($\Gamma \to \mathrm{Y}$, parallel to compression), creating one-dimensional confinement. However, the location and behavior of the valence band maximum (VBM) differs dramatically between the two families.

For sulfides (MoS\textsubscript{2} and WS\textsubscript{2}), the VBM initially resides in the perfectly flat $\Gamma$Y region at the onset of localization. MoS\textsubscript{2} shows onset between 8-9\% compression with the VBM remaining along $\Gamma$Y until 10\%, while WS\textsubscript{2} exhibits earlier onset at 7-8\% with the VBM staying in $\Gamma$Y over a wider range (8-13\%). Beyond these compressions, the VBM jumps to the longitudinal $\Gamma$X direction, where the bands are less flat but still show reasonable confinement. Notably, WS\textsubscript{2} maintains relatively flat bands along $\Gamma$X up to 20\% compression with minimal curvature, while MoS\textsubscript{2} shows increasing curvature beyond 16\% that progressively delocalizes carriers.

Selenides present a strikingly different picture. Neither MoSe\textsubscript{2} nor WSe\textsubscript{2} ever have their VBM in the perfectly flat $\Gamma$Y region. Instead, the VBM always resides along the longitudinal $\Gamma$X direction, which inherently exhibits some dispersion even at the onset of localization. MoSe\textsubscript{2} shows onset at 9-10\% compression, while WSe\textsubscript{2} begins at 10-11\%, both significantly later than their sulfide counterparts. The $\Gamma$X path in selenides is never truly flat, maintaining small but persistent dispersion throughout the compression range. This dispersion increases progressively with compression, creating the characteristic M-shaped valence band profile and limiting the optimal localization range to 10-14\% for MoSe\textsubscript{2} and 10-15\% for WSe\textsubscript{2}.

The density of states evolution (Figure~\ref{fig:tmds_DOS}) follows a clear hierarchy: MoSe\textsubscript{2} > WSe\textsubscript{2} > MoS\textsubscript{2} > WS\textsubscript{2}. Selenides consistently exhibit higher DOS peaks than sulfides, and within each chalcogen family, molybdenum compounds show greater enhancement than tungsten compounds. This hierarchy reflects the number of available electronic states in the flat-band regime, with MoSe\textsubscript{2} providing the highest density of states for potential many-body interactions.

The flatness ratio (Figure~\ref{fig:tmd_alpha}) converges to similar values around 14-15\% for all materials, while the flat bandwidth evolution (Figure~\ref{fig:tmd_Wflat}) shows material-specific trajectories. These metrics, combined with the VBM location analysis, reveal that the apparent similarity in $\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ masks fundamental differences in the nature of localization between sulfides and selenides.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering

\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.48\textwidth}
