\label{fig:tmd_Wflat}
\end{figure}

These observations reveal fundamentally different localization mechanisms and optimal operating regimes for each material family. Table~\ref{tab:tmd_flatband_quantitative} summarizes the key characteristics and application guidelines. WS\textsubscript{2} emerges as the champion for sustained localization, maintaining confinement over the widest compression range (7-20\%) with minimal band curvature. For early-response applications, both sulfides excel due to their low onset thresholds and initial VBM placement in the perfectly flat $\Gamma$Y region. Selenides, despite never achieving true zero-dispersion states, offer the highest DOS enhancement, making them suitable for applications where a high density of states near the Fermi level is more important than perfect flatness.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Comprehensive localization characteristics and application guide}
\label{tab:tmd_flatband_quantitative}
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Material} & \textbf{Onset} & \textbf{Optimal} & \textbf{VBM Location} & \textbf{DOS} & \textbf{Best} \\
& \textbf{Range} & \textbf{Range} & \textbf{Evolution} & \textbf{Rank} & \textbf{Application} \\
\midrule
MoS\textsubscript{2} & 8-9\% & 8-15\% & $\Gamma$Y$\to$$\Gamma$X & 3rd & Early sensing \\
WS\textsubscript{2} & 7-8\% & 7-20\% & $\Gamma$Y$\to$$\Gamma$X & 4th & Sustained localization \\
MoSe\textsubscript{2} & 9-10\% & 10-14\% & Always $\Gamma$X & 1st & High DOS applications \\
WSe\textsubscript{2} & 10-11\% & 10-15\% & Always $\Gamma$X & 2nd & Moderate DOS/flatness \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The fundamental distinction between sulfides and selenides lies not just in their onset compression or degree of flattening, but in the very nature of their electronic confinement. Sulfides achieve true flat-band states with their VBM in perfectly dispersionless regions, while selenides operate in a regime of strong but imperfect confinement with inherent residual dispersion. This dichotomy suggests different optimal applications: sulfides for quantum devices requiring genuine zero-dispersion states, and selenides for applications leveraging high density of states and strong but not perfect confinement.

In the following subsection, we explore the microscopic origins of these contrasting behaviors and their implications for device design.

\section{Curvature Effects and Scaling: The Size-Matters Principle}
\label{section:3.6}

Curvature is the engine of rippletronics, but not all ripples are created equal. Even when two monolayers experience the same level of compressive strain, they can differ dramatically in how strongly they bend—depending on the size of the supercell and the wavelength of the resulting ripple.

To isolate this geometric scaling effect, we compare two MoS\textsubscript{2} supercells under identical compression: a shorter $1 \times 10$ cell and a longer $1 \times 20$ cell. The only difference is ripple wavelength. The resulting contrast in curvature, band gap, and effective mass reveals a striking message: when it comes to quantum confinement, shorter is sharper.

Why? Because for a sinusoidal ripple with amplitude $A$ and wavelength $\lambda$, the maximum curvature \( \kappa_{\mathrm{max}} \) scales as:

\begin{equation}
\kappa_{\mathrm{max}} \sim \frac{A}{\lambda^2}.
\end{equation}

So halving the ripple wavelength (with comparable amplitude) leads to a fourfold increase in curvature. This higher curvature enhances the local deformation potential, deepens the ripple-induced quantum wells, and flattens the valence band more aggressively.\ In our case, the $1 \times 20$ ripple develops twice the amplitude of the $1 \times 10$ ripple ($A_2 = 2A_1$), while having twice the wavelength ($\lambda_2 = 2\lambda_1$). Computing the curvature ratio: \begin{equation} \frac{\kappa_1}{\kappa_2} = \frac{A_1/\lambda_1^2}{A_2/\lambda_2^2} = \frac{A_1/\lambda_1^2}{2A_1/(2\lambda_1)^2} = \frac{A_1/\lambda_1^2}{A_1/2\lambda_1^2} = 2. \end{equation}
Thus, the $1 \times 10$ ripple exhibits twice the curvature of the $1 \times 20$ ripple, despite having half the amplitude. This twofold enhancement in curvature overwhelms the amplitude disadvantage, leading to stronger quantum confinement and more dramatic electronic modulation.

Figure~\ref{fig:supercell_scaling} demonstrates this wavelength dominance. The band gap decreases more rapidly with compression for the shorter wavelength $1 \times 10$ structure, dropping from approximately 1.75 eV to 1.35 eV by 20\% compression, while the $1 \times 20$ structure shows a more gradual decline from 1.75 eV to 1.65 eV. This enhanced gap modulation correlates directly with the maximum curvature evolution: the $1 \times 10$ structure achieves a curvature of 0.18 \AA$^{-1}$ by 20\% compression, more than double the 0.08 \AA$^{-1}$ reached by the $1 \times 20$ cell.

The differential evolution of these parameters explains the distinct electronic behaviors. The $1 \times 10$ structure shows a steeper increase in curvature with compression, while its wavelength decreases more gradually compared to the $1 \times 20$ cell. Conversely, while the $1 \times 20$ structure develops larger amplitude (reaching ~35 \AA vs ~18 \AA for the $1 \times 10$), this amplitude advantage cannot compensate for its longer wavelength in terms of curvature generation.\ Most importantly, examining the band structures (see Appendix A), the onset of localization occurs at 8-9\% compression for the $1 \times 10$ structure, whereas the $1 \times 20$ structure requires 11-12\% compression to achieve the same transition. This confirms that higher curvature directly correlates with earlier onset of quantum confinement—shorter wavelengths require less compression to achieve localization.


\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2_Supercells_Properties.pdf}
\caption[Supercell Scaling Comparison for MoS\textsubscript{2}]{\textbf{Supercell Scaling Comparison for MoS\textsubscript{2}.} Comparison of band gap, ripple amplitude, maximum curvature, and wavelength at varying compression for $1 \times 10$ (shorter wavelength) and $1 \times 20$ (longer wavelength) supercells. The $1 \times 10$ ripple produces greater curvature and stronger band gap reduction despite having smaller amplitude. This demonstrates that wavelength reduction has a more profound impact on electronic properties than amplitude increase.}
\label{fig:supercell_scaling}
\end{figure}

The impact on electronic properties is even more dramatic, as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:effective_masses_supercells}. For the $1 \times 10$ structure, the hole effective mass undergoes a sudden, order-of-magnitude increase between 7-8\% compression, jumping from near-zero to approximately -10 $m_0$ in the $xx$ direction and -13 $m_0$ in the $yy$ direction. This abrupt change coincides with the direct-to-indirect band transition, where the VBM shifts to the $\Gamma$ point and electrons become strongly localized in the quantum wells. The $1 \times 20$ structure exhibits identical behavior but delayed to 12-13\% compression, demonstrating how shorter wavelengths—despite having smaller amplitudes—accelerate the onset of quantum confinement through their enhanced curvature. This 5\% shift in the critical transition point has profound implications for strain engineering: shorter-wavelength ripples can achieve the same electronic modulation at significantly lower applied strains.

Notably, the effective mass anisotropy persists throughout the transition: holes are consistently more massive along the $yy$ direction (parallel to compression) than the $xx$ direction, creating one-dimensional transport characteristics. This anisotropy arises from the complete flattening of bands along the transverse direction while maintaining some dispersion longitudinally. Table~\ref{tab:supercell_comparison} quantifies these differences at 10\% compression—a point where the $1 \times 10$ structure has undergone the direct-indirect transition while the $1 \times 20$ structure remains direct.

To summarize these differences, Table~\ref{tab:supercell_comparison} summarizes the key properties illustrating the curvature effect on localization.


\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Figures/MoS2_effective_masses_grid.pdf}
\caption[Effective Mass Dependence on Curvature in MoS\textsubscript{2}]{\textbf{Effective Masses and Their Dependence on Curvature.} Evolution of electron (CBM) and hole (VBM) effective masses for $1 \times 10$ (left) and $1 \times 20$ (right) supercells. The dramatic increase in hole mass at the direct-indirect transition occurs at 7-8\% for the shorter wavelength and 12-13\% for the longer wavelength structure.}
\label{fig:effective_masses_supercells}
\end{figure}


\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption[\texorpdfstring{$1 \times 10$ vs.\ $1 \times 20$ MoS\textsubscript{2} Supercells}{Comparison of MoS2 Supercells}]
{\textbf{Comparison of $1 \times 10$ and $1 \times 20$ MoS\textsubscript{2} Supercells at 10\% Compression.} Short-wavelength ripples in the smaller supercell exhibit higher curvature and have already undergone the localization transition, while long-wavelength structures in the larger supercell remain in the delocalized regime.}
\label{tab:supercell_comparison}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{$1 \times 10$} & \textbf{$1 \times 20$} \\
\midrule
Amplitude & Low & High \\
Wavelength & Short & Long \\
Curvature & High & Low \\
Band Character & Indirect & Indirect \\
Onset of Localization & Early & Late \\
Localization Strength & Strong & Strong \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}



\subsection*{Summary: Mechanical Design of Quantum Landscapes}

Chapter 3 has established rippletronics as a new paradigm for engineering quantum materials through mechanical deformation. We have shown how simple uniaxial compression transforms a flat TMD monolayer into a periodic ripple structure, creating a strain superlattice that fundamentally reshapes the electronic landscape, all without chemical modification or interlayer assembly.

Our systematic exploration revealed three core principles:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Geometric control of bands:} As compression increases, the ripple curvature $\kappa$ drives electronic localization. The valence band flattens progressively, effective mass diverges, and states become confined to regions of maximum curvature—effectively creating an array of self-assembled quantum wells.
  
  \item \textbf{Material-specific responses:} Each TMD exhibits unique localization behavior. Sulfides achieve true flat bands with VBM in perfectly dispersionless regions, while selenides operate in a regime of strong but imperfect confinement. The hierarchy of responses (onset compression, DOS enhancement, optimal operating range) provides a tunable palette for device design.
  
  \item \textbf{Wavelength trumps amplitude:} Shorter ripples create stronger quantum confinement despite having smaller amplitudes. The $1 \times 10$ structure requires 3-4\% less compression than the $1 \times 20$ structure to achieve the same electronic transition, demonstrating that curvature—scaling as $\kappa \sim A/\lambda^2$—is the master variable controlling localization.
\end{enumerate}

By mapping the complete phase diagram from delocalized to strongly localized states, we have established mechanical strain as a continuous, reversible, and scalable route to flat-band physics. In the next chapter, we will push these concepts to their extreme: exploring what happens when compression drives the material beyond simple rippling into more complex geometrical phases, unlocking new degrees of freedom for quantum engineering.

\chapter{Conclusion and Outlook}

\section{Introduction}

This dissertation has explored the use of mechanical strain engineering---specifically, periodic ripple formation---as a novel route for creating flat electronic bands in monolayer transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDs). By leveraging the exceptional mechanical flexibility of atomically thin materials, we demonstrated that controlled uniaxial compression can induce periodic strain profiles that profoundly alter the electronic structure. Unlike traditional approaches such as moiré engineering in twisted bilayer systems, strain-induced flat bands offer a dynamically tunable and fabrication-friendly alternative for accessing strongly correlated electronic phases.

The concept of \emph{rippletronics} proposed here provides a versatile, scalable, and experimentally feasible method for flat-band engineering. Instead of relying on twist angles or interlayer stacking, rippletronics utilizes single-layer mechanical deformation, offering a pathway to band flattening that is robust and accessible. This development has significant implications for future 2D material-based devices and quantum systems. Through large-scale atomistic simulations and first-principles calculations, we demonstrated that monolayer TMDs under uniaxial compression undergo a well-defined evolutionary sequence shown in Figure~\ref{fig:ripple_sequence}.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    node distance=1.3cm and 1.2cm,
    every node/.style={
        draw,
        rectangle,
        rounded corners,
        minimum height=1.1cm,
        minimum width=2.9cm,
        align=center,
        font=\small,
        text=black
    },
    shorten >=3pt, shorten <=3pt
    ]
\node[fill=orange!10!white] (comp) {Compression};
\node[fill=orange!20!white, right=of comp] (buck) {Buckling\\(Transition)};
\node[fill=orange!30!white, right=of buck] (ripple) {Ripple\\Formation\\(Curvature)};
\node[fill=orange!50!white, right=of ripple] (flat) {Band\\Flattening\\(Hole\\Localization)};
\foreach \i/\j in {comp/buck, buck/ripple, ripple/flat}
    \draw[->, thick] (\i) -- (\j);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Schematic illustrating the progression from uniaxial compression in a monolayer TMD to ripple formation and valence band flattening. The intensifying orange color indicates the growing degree of structural and electronic transformation.}
\label{fig:ripple_sequence}
\end{figure}

\section{Summary of Key Findings}

Through systematic investigation combining atomistic simulations and first-principles calculations, this work has revealed the fundamental mechanisms by which mechanical deformation creates flat electronic bands in monolayer TMDs. The key findings are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:key_findings}.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption{Summary of key findings in rippletronics-based flat-band engineering}
\label{tab:key_findings}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Category} & \textbf{Key Points} & \textbf{Implications} \\ \midrule
Flat-band formation & \makecell[l]{Compression induces periodic\\ ripples in monolayer TMDs} & \makecell[l]{Strain fields flatten bands\\ and enhance electron interactions} \\
Carrier localization & \makecell[l]{Ripple crests/troughs trap holes\\ acting as quantum wells} & \makecell[l]{Supports emergence of\\ strongly correlated states} \\
Material trends & \makecell[l]{Sulfides achieve true flat bands\\ Selenides show imperfect confinement} & \makecell[l]{Material-specific design rules\\ for targeted applications} \\
Wavelength effects & \makecell[l]{Shorter ripples produce stronger\\ confinement despite smaller amplitude} & \makecell[l]{Curvature ($\kappa \sim A/\lambda^2$)\\ governs localization} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The structural evolution follows a clear sequence from initial compression through buckling to ripple formation and ultimately electronic reconstruction. Beyond critical compression thresholds of 7--8\%, monolayer TMDs spontaneously form periodic ripple patterns with wavelengths determined by the supercell geometry. The ripple amplitude increases steadily with compression while wavelength contracts, yielding a nonlinear enhancement in curvature that scales as $\kappa \sim A/\lambda^2$. This geometric transformation directly maps onto electronic changes: the valence band undergoes dramatic flattening near the $\Gamma$ point, accompanied by a direct-to-indirect band gap transition and an order-of-magnitude increase in hole effective mass.

\section{Rippletronics vs. Twistronics: A Comparative Perspective}

Both moiré superlattices (twistronics) and rippletronics exploit periodic potentials to engineer flat bands, crucial for exploring strongly correlated electron phenomena. However, these approaches differ fundamentally in their physical mechanisms, experimental requirements, and scalability, as detailed in Table~\ref{tab:compare_methods}.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption{Comparison between moiré engineering (twistronics) and rippletronics for generating flat bands}
\label{tab:compare_methods}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Feature} & \textbf{Twistronics} & \textbf{Rippletronics} \\ \midrule
Mechanism & Interlayer rotation/mismatch & Single-layer compression \\
Material requirements & Stacked bilayers & Single monolayer \\
Tunability & Fixed by twist angle & Continuous via strain \\
Experimental complexity & High (precise alignment) & Moderate (strain control) \\
Disorder sensitivity & High (twist angle variations) & Low (no stacking faults) \\
Dynamic control & Static after fabrication & Real-time adjustable \\
Scalability & Limited by alignment precision & Highly scalable \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The mechanical simplicity of rippletronics provides several practical advantages. While twistronics requires precise angular alignment between layers and remains sensitive to small variations in twist angle, rippletronics operates on a single layer with continuous tunability through mechanical strain. This approach eliminates concerns about interlayer disorder and stacking faults while offering real-time control over electronic properties through strain modulation.

\section{Important Insights and Considerations}

Several crucial aspects emerge from our systematic investigation of ripple-induced flat bands. The selective localization of holes versus electrons reveals fundamental differences in orbital sensitivity to curvature. Hole states, dominated by Mo $d_{z^2}$ and S $p$ orbitals, show exceptional sensitivity to curvature-induced bond angle changes, becoming trapped at ripple extrema. In contrast, conduction band electrons maintain their dispersive character under similar deformation, creating an intrinsic electron-hole asymmetry that could be exploited for device applications.

Regarding experimental feasibility, the critical compressions predicted for flat-band formation (7--15\%) fall within reported mechanical limits for TMD monolayers. Published studies indicate fracture strains of 6--11\% for monolayer MoS\textsubscript{2}, placing our predictions in the experimentally viable range. Multiple pathways exist for achieving the required strain levels, including substrate-induced compression via thermal mismatch, flexible platforms, localized nanoindentation, and pre-patterned substrates.

While GGA functionals underestimate absolute band gaps, the relative trends remain robust. The gap reduction with compression, direct-to-indirect transitions, and valence band flattening patterns are preserved even with more sophisticated theoretical treatments. This consistency ensures that our qualitative predictions about electronic evolution remain reliable despite quantitative uncertainties in absolute energy scales.

\section{Robustness and Practical Considerations}

The robustness of ripple-induced flat bands to external perturbations represents a critical factor for practical applications. Although our calculations were performed without explicit spin-orbit coupling (SOC), the fundamental localization mechanism should remain intact under its inclusion. Previous work on TMDs indicates that SOC primarily splits the valence bands at the K point by 100--400 meV without preventing the strain-driven emergence of $\Gamma$-dominated flat bands. The introduction of SOC would add spin-dependent physics relevant for spintronic applications while preserving the core rippletronics phenomena.

Thermal stability analysis suggests promising prospects for room-temperature operation. The energy scale of strain-induced potential modulation, approximately 100 meV based on our band structure calculations, substantially exceeds thermal energy at room temperature ($k_BT \sim 25$ meV). While thermal fluctuations may broaden the sharp features of localized states, the underlying quantum confinement should persist under ambient conditions, maintaining the essential characteristics needed for device functionality.

\section{Future Directions and Applications}

The demonstration of strain-induced flat bands in monolayer TMDs opens numerous research avenues spanning fundamental physics to practical applications. Immediate opportunities include experimental validation through advanced characterization techniques such as scanning tunneling microscopy, angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy, and transport measurements. These experiments will be crucial for confirming the predicted electronic structure modifications and establishing the practical limits of the approach.

The curvature-defined quantum wells at ripple extrema suggest applications as arrays of quantum emitters, potentially enabling deterministic single-photon sources without chemical defects. The enhanced density of states and reduced kinetic energy in flat-band regions provide an ideal platform for exploring strongly correlated electron physics, including Mott insulating states, Wigner crystallization, and unconventional superconductivity. The extreme mass anisotropy creates quasi-one-dimensional channels that may exhibit exotic transport phenomena such as Luttinger liquid behavior.

Looking beyond TMDs, this mechanical approach to band engineering could extend to other two-dimensional materials including graphene, black phosphorus, and topological insulators, each offering unique electronic properties for strain modulation. The possibility of combining ripple engineering with moiré physics in multilayer heterostructures presents opportunities for creating hybrid quantum systems with multiple tuning parameters. Real-time strain control through piezoelectric substrates or mechanical actuators could enable dynamic manipulation of electronic properties, leading to a new class of strain-programmable quantum devices.

\section{Broader Implications}

Rippletronics represents a paradigm shift in materials design, elevating mechanical deformation from a perturbation to be minimized to a primary design tool. This approach demonstrates that geometry can directly program quantum mechanical behavior, offering continuous and reversible control over electronic properties. The ability to achieve flat-band physics in single layers without complex stacking or alignment procedures significantly reduces fabrication complexity while maintaining the essential physics needed for quantum applications.

The convergence of mechanical and quantum engineering embodied in this work suggests new possibilities for materials design. By treating strain not as an unwanted effect but as a functional parameter, we expand the design space for quantum materials. This perspective aligns with broader trends in condensed matter physics toward mechanical control of quantum properties, including recent advances in strain-tuned superconductivity and topological phases.

\section{Closing Remarks}

This dissertation has established rippletronics as a powerful paradigm for engineering flat electronic bands through periodic mechanical deformation. By demonstrating that simple uniaxial compression can transform uniform monolayers into programmable quantum landscapes, we have expanded the toolbox for designing strongly correlated electronic systems. The work bridges traditionally separate fields of mechanics and quantum physics, showing how structural engineering at the nanoscale enables direct control over electronic functionality.

The elegance of rippletronics lies in its simplicity: compression creates ripples, ripples create curvature, and curvature reshapes the quantum world. This direct mapping from mechanical input to quantum output offers a level of control and tunability that complements existing approaches while opening new directions for research. As we continue exploring the rich interplay between geometry and quantum mechanics, rippletronics stands as a testament to the power of interdisciplinary thinking in advancing our understanding and control of quantum materials.


\chapter*{Glossary of Technical Terms}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Glossary of Technical Terms} % Adds to table of contents

\begin{description}[leftmargin=0.5in,labelsep=0.2in,font=\normalfont\bfseries]
\item[2D materials / monolayer] Atomically thin crystals consisting of a single layer of atoms. Example: monolayer MoS$_2$ is a 2D material one molecule thick.
\item[TMD (Transition Metal Dichalcogenide)] A family of layered compounds with formula MX$_2$ (M = transition metal like Mo, W; X = chalcogen like S, Se). They often have a layered structure and can be thinned to monolayers.
\item[Flat band] An electronic band with very little dispersion (nearly constant energy as a function of momentum). Electrons in a flat band have a very large effective mass and a high density of states.
\item[Effective mass] A quantity ($m^*$) describing how the acceleration of an electron in a crystal responds to forces, defined by the curvature of the electronic band. A heavy effective mass means the band is flat (electrons behave sluggishly).
\item[Brillouin zone (BZ)] The fundamental domain of the reciprocal lattice of a periodic crystal. High-symmetry points (like $\Gamma$, $\mathrm{K}$, $M$ in a hexagonal lattice) are points of symmetry in momentum space.
\item[Valence band maximum (VBM)] The highest energy state of the valence band (highest occupied state at zero temperature in a semiconductor).
\item[Conduction band minimum (CBM)] The lowest energy state of the conduction band (lowest unoccupied state in a semiconductor).
\item[Direct/Indirect band gap] A direct gap means the VBM and CBM occur at the same momentum ($\mathbf{k}$) in the BZ, allowing direct optical transitions. Indirect means they occur at different $\mathbf{k}$, requiring a phonon for optical transition.
\item[Density of states (DOS)] The number of electronic states per interval of energy at each energy level, often expressed as states per eV per unit cell. Peaks in DOS can indicate flat bands or van Hove singularities.
\item[DFT (Density Functional Theory)] A quantum mechanical computational method used to calculate electronic structure, treating the many-electron problem in a mean-field manner via electron density.
\item[GGA-PBE] A specific choice of exchange-correlation functional within DFT (Generalized Gradient Approximation by Perdew, Burke, and Ernzerhof) known for reasonable accuracy in solid-state systems.
\item[Band folding] The mapping of energy bands into a smaller Brillouin zone when using a supercell larger than the primitive cell. States that were at different $\mathbf{k}$ in the primitive cell may appear at the same $\mathbf{k}$ in the supercell BZ.
\item[Buckling] An out-of-plane deformation of a 2D material under compressive strain, forming a wavy or corrugated shape (a ripple).
\item[Curvature] In the context of a ripple, the second derivative of the out-of-plane displacement with respect to position. High curvature indicates a sharply bent region.
\item[Heavy fermion] A quasiparticle in certain intermetallic compounds that behaves as if it has an extremely large effective mass (due to strong electron-electron interactions).
\item[Lateral heterostructure] A junction of two different regions within the same 2D material with distinct properties (e.g., due to strain or doping).
\item[Flatness ratio] A metric quantifying the fraction of the Brillouin zone over which the valence band is nearly flat. Indicates the extent of real-space localization.
\item[Localization] The confinement of electronic wavefunctions in real space, typically due to geometric or potential variations like curvature or strain.
\item[Rippletronics] An emerging field in 2D materials where periodic mechanical rippling modifies the electronic structure, enabling flat bands and localization effects.
\item[Twistronics] A field in 2D materials where twisting two stacked layers produces moir\'e superlattices and emergent flat bands due to interlayer interference.
\end{description}

\chapter*{List of Symbols and Notations}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{List of Symbols and Notations} % Adds to table of contents

\begin{longtable}{p{3cm} p{12cm}}
\toprule
$E_n(\mathbf{k})$ & Energy of the $n$-th electronic band as a function of wavevector $\mathbf{k}$. \\
VBM & Valence band maximum (highest occupied band energy in the semiconductor). \\
CBM & Conduction band minimum (lowest unoccupied band energy). \\
$\mathrm{K}$, $\Gamma$, $M$ & High-symmetry points in the primitive Brillouin zone of a hexagonal lattice (corner, center, edge-midpoint, respectively). \\
$a$ & Lattice constant of monolayer MoS$_2$ (approximately 3.16~\AA). \\
$N$ & Multiple of the primitive cell in the supercell (e.g., $1\times N$ means the supercell is $N$ times longer in one direction than the primitive cell). \\
$C$ & Compressive strain in percent, defined as $C = -100 (\Delta L/L_0)$, where a positive $C$ denotes compression. \\
$L_0$ & Initial length of the supercell (uncompressed). \\
$\Delta L$ & Change in length of the supercell under strain ($L - L_0$). \\
$\kappa$ & Curvature of the ripple. $\kappa_{\max}$ indicates the maximum curvature (at ripple peaks). Units of curvature are inverse length. \\
$A$ & Amplitude of the ripple (height from the center plane to a peak). \\
$\lambda$ & Wavelength of the ripple (distance between equivalent points, such as peak to peak). \\
$m^*$ & Effective mass of a charge carrier. $m^*_{xx}$, $m^*_{yy}$ denote components along $x$ or $y$ directions. Given in units of the free electron mass $m_0$. \\
$\hbar$ & Reduced Planck constant ($h/2\pi$), often appearing in quantum expressions like the effective mass formula. \\
$\mathbf{k}$ & Crystal momentum (wavevector) in reciprocal space. \\
$E_g$ & Band gap energy (energy difference between CBM and VBM). \\
PDOS & Projected Density of States (density of states projected onto specific atoms or orbitals). \\
$W_{\mathrm{flat}}$ & Bandwidth of the flat region in the valence band. Smaller values indicate stronger localization. \\
$\alpha_{\mathrm{flat}}$ & Flatness ratio---the fraction of the Brillouin zone over which the valence band is nearly flat. \\
$\mu$ & Carrier mobility (proportional to $1/m^*$ for constant scattering time). \\
\bottomrule
\end{longtable}


